{"title_page": "2018 College Football Playoff National Championship", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox NCAA football yearly game\n| Game Name          = College Football Playoff National Championship\n| Optional Subheader = 4th College Football Playoff National Championship\n| Title Sponsor      =\n| Image              = CFP Atlanta 2018 logo.svg\n| Image_Size         = 175\n| Image_Upright      =\n| Alt                =\n| Caption            =\n| Date Game Played   = January 8\n| Year Game Played   = 2018\n| Football Season    = 2017\n| Stadium            = [[Mercedes-Benz Stadium]]\n| City               = [[Atlanta|Atlanta, Georgia]]\n| Visitor School     = University of Alabama\n| Visitor Name Short = Alabama\n| Visitor Nickname   = Crimson Tide\n| Visitor Record     = 12-1\n| Visitor Conference = [[American Athletic Conference|SEC]]\n| Visitor AP         = 4\n| Visitor Coaches    = 4\n| Visitor CFP        = 4\n| Visitor Coach      = [[Nick Saban]]\n| Visitor1           = 0\n| Visitor2           = 0\n| Visitor3           = 10\n| Visitor4           = 10\n| Visitor5           = 6\n| Home School        = University of Georgia\n| Home Name Short    = Georgia\n| Home Nickname      = Bulldogs\n| Home Record        = 13\u20131\n| Home Conference    = SEC\n| Home AP            = 3\n| Home Coaches       = 3\n| Home CFP           = 3\n| Home Coach         = [[Kirby Smart]]\n| Home1              = 0\n| Home2              = 13\n| Home3              = 7\n| Home4              = 0\n| Home5              = 3\n| MVP                = Offensive: #13 QB [[Tua Tagovailoa]], Fr. Alabama<br>Defensive: #94 DT [[Daron Payne]], Jr. Alabama\n| Odds               = Alabama by 3.5\n| Anthem             = [[Zac Brown Band]]\n| Referee            = Dan Capron ([[Big Ten Conference|Big Ten]])<ref>{{cite news|last=Kirshner|first=Alex|title=A Big Ten officiating crew is working the all-SEC National Championship|url=https://www.sbnation.com/college-football/2018/1/8/16860896/national-championship-referees-officials-alabama-georgia-2018|publisher=[[SB Nation]]|website=SBNation.com|date=January 8, 2018|access-date=January 8, 2018}}</ref>\n| Halftime           = [[Georgia Redcoat Marching Band]]<br>[[Million Dollar Band (marching band)|Million Dollar Band]]<!-- Do not add Kendrick Lamar. This halftime show is an invention of the broadcast rightsholder and is not the official on-field event. -->\n| Attendance         = 77,430\n| Payout             = \n| US Network         = [[ESPN College Football|ESPN]] and [[ESPN Radio]]\n| US Announcers      = [[Chris Fowler]] (play-by-play)<br>[[Kirk Herbstreit]] (analyst)<br>[[Maria Taylor (analyst)|Maria Taylor]] and [[Tom Rinaldi]] (sideline) (ESPN)<br>[[Sean McDonough]], [[Todd Blackledge]], [[Holly Rowe]] and Ian Fitzsimmons (ESPN Radio)\n| Ratings            = 16.7 (28.44 million viewers)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://espnmediazone.com/us/press-releases/2018/01/epic-college-football-playoff-national-championship-delivers-massive-16-7-overnight-9-year-year/ |title=Epic College Football Playoff National Championship Delivers Massive 16.7 Overnight, Up 9% Year-Over-Year |last=Volner |first=Derek |date=January 9, 2018 |website=www.espnmediazone.com |publisher=ESPN MediaZone |access-date=December 4, 2018}}</ref>\n| Intl Network       = [[ESPN Deportes]]<br>[[ESPN Deportes Radio]]\n| Intl Announcers    = [[Eduardo Varela|Lalo Varela]] and Pablo Viruega (ESPN Deportes)<br>[[Kenneth Garay]] and Sebastian Martinez (ESPN Deportes Radio)\n}}\n\nThe '''2018 College Football Playoff National Championship''' was a [[college football]] [[bowl game]] that determined a [[College football national championships in NCAA Division I FBS|national champion]] in the [[NCAA Division I Football Bowl Subdivision]] for the [[2017 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2017 season]]. The [[2017 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|Alabama Crimson Tide]] defeated the [[2017 Georgia Bulldogs football team|Georgia Bulldogs]] 26\u201323, coming back from a 13\u20130 deficit at [[halftime]] to secure the win in overtime. True freshman quarterback [[Tua Tagovailoa]] and defensive tackle [[Daron Payne]] were respectively named the offensive and defensive players of the game.\n\nThe College Football Playoff selection committee chose the semifinalists following the conclusion of the 2017 regular season. Alabama and Georgia advanced to the national championship after winning the semifinal games hosted by the [[Sugar Bowl]] and [[Rose Bowl Game]] respectively in January 2018. The championship game was played at [[Mercedes-Benz Stadium]] in [[Atlanta|Atlanta, Georgia]] on January 8, 2018.\n\n==Background==\n[[File:Mercedes-Benz Stadium, Jan 2018.jpg|thumb|The 2018 College Football Playoff National Championship took place at [[Mercedes-Benz Stadium]]]]\nThe [[Mercedes-Benz Stadium]] in [[Atlanta]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] was announced as the host site for the fourth College Football National Championship on November 4, 2015.<ref name=\"future sites\">{{cite web|title=Atlanta, Santa Clara and New Orleans land CFP title games for 2018\u201320|author=Alex Scarbrough|publisher=ESPN.com|date=November 4, 2015|accessdate=November 4, 2015|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/id/14052099/atlanta-santa-clara-new-orleans-land-cfp-title-games-2018-20}}</ref>\n\n==2018 College Football Playoff==\n{{2018 College Football Playoff}}\n\nThe [[College Football Playoff]] (CFP) selection committee selected four teams to advance to the playoff: the [[2017 Clemson Tigers football team|Clemson Tigers]], [[2017 Oklahoma Sooners football team|Oklahoma Sooners]], [[2017 Georgia Bulldogs football team|Georgia Bulldogs]], and [[2017 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|Alabama Crimson Tide]].<ref name=final>{{cite web|url=http://collegefootballplayoff.com/documents/2017/12/3/Final_Top_25_College_Football_Playoff_Selection_Day.pdf |title=Selection Committee Rankings: Final Top 25 Rankings |website=College Football Playoff |date=December 3, 2017|access-date=December 3, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Teams==\n===Alabama===\n{{See also|2017 Alabama Crimson Tide football team}}\nThe [[Alabama Crimson Tide football|Alabama Crimson Tide]] defeated the [[Clemson Tigers football|Clemson Tigers]] in the [[2018 Sugar Bowl]] by a score of 24\u20136 to reach the championship game. The Tide had a 12\u20131 season, becoming the SEC West Division co-champions with the [[2017 Auburn Tigers football team|Auburn Tigers]]. The Crimson Tide were coached by [[Nick Saban]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Alabama's Sugar Bowl win against Clemson sets up all-SEC final: Final score, stats, analysis|url=http://www.nola.com/lsu/index.ssf/2018/01/alabama_clemson_sugar_bowl_201.html|publisher=nola.com|date=January 1, 2018|accessdate=January 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Georgia===\n{{See also|2017 Georgia Bulldogs football team}}\nThe [[Georgia Bulldogs football|Georgia Bulldogs]] defeated the [[Oklahoma Sooners football|Oklahoma Sooners]] in the [[2018 Rose Bowl]] by a score of 54\u201348 in double [[overtime (sports)|overtime]] to reach the championship game. The Bulldogs had a 13\u20131 season claiming their 13th [[Southeastern Conference]] (SEC) championship with a rematch victory over the [[Auburn Tigers football|Auburn Tigers]], 28\u20137. The Bulldogs were coached by [[Kirby Smart]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Emerson|first1=Seth|title=Georgia to play for national championship after Rose Bowl win in 2 OT|url=http://www.ajc.com/sports/college-football/georgia-wins-bulldogs-play-for-national-championship-rose-bowl-victory-2ot/0KS2iwglhAtfBE2XXsSQ3N/|publisher=ajc.com|date=January 1, 2018|accessdate=January 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Starting lineups==\n[[File:Nick Saban, who is the Alabama team coach, gives interviews and watches all the plays during this important spring scrimmage at University of Alabama, Tuscaloosa, Alabama LCCN2010638313 (cropped).jpg|thumb|left|upright|Alabama head coach [[Nick Saban]]]]\n[[File:Kirby Smart Jan 2018.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Georgia head coach [[Kirby Smart]]]]\n<center>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size: 95%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:200px;\" style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Alabama Crimson Tide}};\" | Alabama !! Position !! Position !! style=\"{{NCAA secondary color cell|Georgia Bulldogs}};\"|Georgia\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center\"|'''Offense'''\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"#FFCC00\" | [[Calvin Ridley]] 1 || colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\"| [[wide receiver|WR]] || bgcolor=\"#FFCC00\" | [[Javon Wims]] 7\n|-\n| [[Cam Sims]] || colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\"| [[wide receiver|WR]] || bgcolor=\"#FFCC00\" | [[Riley Ridley]] 4\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"#FFCC00\" | [[Jonah Williams]] 1 || colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\"| [[left tackle|LT]] || bgcolor=\"#FFCC00\" | [[Isaiah Wynn]] 1\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"#FFCC00\" | [[Ross Pierschbacher]] 5 || colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\"| [[left guard|LG]] || Kendall Baker\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"#FFCC00\" | [[Bradley Bozeman]] 6 || colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\"| [[center (American football)|C]] || bgcolor=\"#FFCC00\" |  [[Lamont Gaillard]] 6\n|-\n| [[J. C. Hassenauer]] || colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\"| [[right guard|RG]] ||  Ben Cleveland\n|-\n| Matt Womack || colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\"| [[right tackle|RT]] || bgcolor=\"#FFCC00\" | [[Andrew Thomas (American football)|Andrew Thomas]] 1\n|-\n| [[Hale Hentges]] || style=\"text-align:center\"| [[tight end|TE]] || style=\"text-align:center\"| [[Halfback (American football)|TB]] || bgcolor=\"#FFCC00\" | [[Nick Chubb]] 2\n|-\n| [[Robert Foster (American football)|Robert Foster]] || colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\"| WR || bgcolor=\"#FFCC00\" | [[Terry Godwin]] 7\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"#FFCC00\" | [[Jalen Hurts]] 2 || colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\"| [[quarterback|QB]] || bgcolor=\"#FFCC00\" | [[Jake Fromm]] 5\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"#FFCC00\" | [[Damien Harris]] 3 || colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\"| [[running back|RB]] || bgcolor=\"#FFCC00\" | [[Sony Michel]] 1\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center\"|'''Defense''' \n|-\n| bgcolor=\"#FFCC00\" | [[Da'Shawn Hand]] 4 || colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\"| [[defensive end|DE]] || David Marshall\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"#FFCC00\" | [[Daron Payne]] 1 || colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\"| [[nose guard|NG]] || [[John Atkins (American football)|John Atkins]]\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"#FFCC00\" | [[Isaiah Buggs]] 6 || style=\"text-align:center\"| [[Defensive line|DL]] || style=\"text-align:center\"| [[defensive tackle|DT]] || Tyler Clark\n|-\n| bgcolor=\u201c#FFCC00\u201d | [[Terrell Lewis (American football)|Terrell Lewis]] 3 || style=\"text-align:center\"| [[strongside linebacker|SLB]] || style=\"text-align:center\"| [[Linebacker|LB]] || [[Davin Bellamy]]\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"#FFCC00\" | [[Mack Wilson]] 5 || style=\"text-align:center\"| [[middle linebacker|MLB]] || style=\"text-align:center\"| LB || Reggie Carter \n|-\n| bgcolor=\"#FFCC00\" | [[Rashaan Evans]] 1 || style=\"text-align:center\"| [[weakside linebacker|WLB]] || style=\"text-align:center\"| LB || bgcolor=\"#FFCC00\" | \u2020 [[Roquan Smith]] 1\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"#FFCC00\" | [[Deionte Thompson]] 5 || colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\"| [[Defensive back|DB]] || Malkom Parrish\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"#FFCC00\" | [[Anthony Averett]] 4 || colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\"| [[Cornerback|CB]] || bgcolor=\"#FFCC00\" | [[Deandre Baker]] 1\n|-\n| [[Levi Wallace (American football)|Levi Wallace]] || colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\"| CB || Aaron Davis\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"#FFCC00\" | \u2020 [[Minkah Fitzpatrick]] 1 || style=\"text-align:center\"| [[strong safety|SS]] || style=\"text-align:center\"| [[Safety (gridiron football position)|S]] || Dominick Sanders\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"#FFCC00\" | [[Ronnie Harrison]] 3 || style=\"text-align:center\"| [[free safety|FS]] || style=\"text-align:center\"| CB || J.R Reed\n|-\n| colspan=4 align=center | \u2020 = 2017 All-American\n|-\n| colspan=4 align=center | {{hilite|Selected in an NFL Draft|#FFCC00}}<br>(number corresponds to draft round) \n|}\n</center>\nSource:<ref>{{cite web |url=https://rolltide.com/documents/2018/1/8//2018CFP_GameBook.pdf |title=CFP National Championship Game Book |page=5 |via=rolltide.com |date=January 8, 2018 |accessdate=January 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Game summary==\nAfter winning the [[coin toss]], Alabama deferred to the second half and Georgia received the ball to begin the game. After two plays, quarterback [[Jake Fromm]] attempted a pass downfield and was intercepted by Tony Brown. Alabama began their first drive of the game, and, after eleven plays, that drive ended with kicker Andy Pappanastos missing a 40-yard [[field goal]]. The teams each had [[three-and-out]]s for the game's first two [[Punt (gridiron football)|punts]]. During Georgia's ensuing drive, the quarter ended, with no score.<ref name=nytlive>{{cite news|last1=Hoffman|first1=Benjamin|last2=Drape|first2=Joe|last3=Tracy|first3=Marc|title=National Championship Game: Georgia vs. Alabama Live Score|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/01/08/sports/national-championship-game-alabama-georgia.html|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=January 8, 2018|accessdate=January 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter a failed third down conversion, on the second play of the second quarter, Georgia kicker [[Rodrigo Blankenship]] hit a 41-yard field goal to open the scoring and put Georgia in the lead by three. Alabama's ensuing drive went nowhere, as they gained four yards on three plays and punted. Georgia took the ball and drove down the field, and found themselves with a first and goal at the Alabama 10-yard-line; the Tide defense held, however, and the Bulldogs settled for a second field goal and took a 6\u20130 lead with just over seven and a half minutes until half. On Alabama's next drive, the Georgia defense held yet again and Alabama's [[JK Scott]] punted for the third time. Just prior to the punt, Georgia wide receiver Javon Wims was shown walking to the locker room, reportedly with a left shoulder injury. Both defenses then forced punts, and Georgia took back over with 1:19 remaining in the half on their own 31-yard-line. Nine plays later, on Alabama's 1-yard-line, [[Mecole Hardman]] took a direct snap, faked a handoff, and ran into the end zone for the game's first touchdown, putting Georgia up 13\u20130 going into [[halftime]].<ref name=nytlive/>\n\nBecause they deferred the coin toss, Alabama received the ball first in the second half. They started their drive on their own 22-yard-line. [[Tua Tagovailoa]], Alabama's backup quarterback, started the second half for the Tide; that drive quickly resulted in a three-and-out. The initial punt was blocked, but an erroneous offside call gave the Tide another chance to punt. Georgia started their drive on their own 36-yard-line, but punted on 4th & 17. Alabama took over on their own 44-yard-line.<ref name=nytlive/> The teams then traded touchdowns on consecutive drives; Alabama scored their first points of the game on a 6-yard pass from Tagovailoa to Ruggs, but Georgia immediately responded with an 80-yard touchdown connection from Fromm to Mecole Hardman, putting Georgia up 20\u20137. On the second play of Alabama's ensuing drive, Tagovailoa, while scrambling to the left, threw into traffic and was intercepted by Georgia's Deandre Baker. Up 13, the Bulldogs took over possession of the ball on Alabama's 39-yard-line. The Tide defense responded immediately, however, as [[Raekwon Davis]] intercepted a Jake Fromm pass on the first play of Georgia's drive, returning the pick to the UGA 40-yard-line. The Tide gained fifteen yards on six plays and kicker Andy Pappanastos avenged his earlier miss with a 43-yard field goal that put Bama within ten. The teams then traded punts. Just prior to Alabama's punt, it was announced that an Alabama defensive back, Kyriq McDonald, had collapsed on the sideline; the situation was described as a \"serious medical emergency\". He was loaded onto a medical stretcher awake and conscious. Georgia could not muster anything on offense that drive, and punted. The fourth quarter saw Tagovailoa lead the Tide to come back and tie the game at 20 with 3:49. With three seconds remaining in the game, Andy Pappanastos missed a potential game-winning 36-yard field goal to the left, sending the game to overtime.<ref name=nytlive/>\n\nIn overtime, Georgia had an unsuccessful drive that resulted in both a three-and-out, and a 13-yard loss sack to Fromm.  Georgia opted to attempt a 51-yard field goal, which they successfully made. On Alabama's first offensive play in overtime, Tagovailoa was sacked for a 16-yard loss, but immediately followed that with a game-winning 41-yard touchdown pass to [[DeVonta Smith]], in a play that has since been called \"2nd and 26\" by fans.<ref name=nytlive/> Tagovailoa was named the offensive player of the game, and [[Daron Payne]] was named the defensive player of the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ncaaf/2018/01/09/cfp-players-game-alabamas-tua-tagovailoa-and-daron-payne/1015832001/|title=CFP players of the game: Alabama's Tua Tagovailoa and Daron Payne|first=A.J.|last=Perez|work=USA Today|date=January 9, 2018|accessdate=January 9, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Scoring summary===\n{{AmFootballScoreSummaryStart|VisitorName=Alabama|HomeName=Georgia|state=}}\n{{AmFootballScoreSummaryEntry\n| Quarter=2\n| Time=14:14\n| Team=Georgia\n| DrivePlays=14\n| DriveLength=55\n| DriveTime=7:40\n| Type=FG\n| yards=41\n| Kicker=[[Rodrigo Blankenship]]\n| Visitor=0\n| Home=3\n}}\n{{AmFootballScoreSummaryEntry\n| Quarter=2\n| Time=7:33\n| Team=Georgia\n| DrivePlays=13\n| DriveLength=70\n| DriveTime=5:19\n| Type=FG\n| yards=27\n| Kicker=Rodrigo Blankenship\n| Visitor=0\n| Home=6\n}}\n{{AmFootballScoreSummaryEntry\n| Quarter=2\n| Time=0:07\n| Team=Georgia\n| DrivePlays=9\n| DriveLength=69\n| DriveTime=1:12\n| Type=RushTD\n| Runner=Mecole Hardman\n| yards=1\n| kickresult=good\n| Kicker=Rodrigo Blankenship\n| Visitor=0\n| Home=13\n}}\n{{AmFootballScoreSummaryEntry\n| Quarter=3\n| Time=8:52\n| Team=Alabama\n| DrivePlays=7\n| DriveLength=56\n| DriveTime=1:59\n| Type=RecTD\n| Receiver=[[Henry Ruggs|Henry Ruggs III]]\n| QB=[[Tua Tagovailoa]]\n| yards=6\n| kickresult=good\n| Kicker=Andy Pappanastos\n| Visitor=7\n| Home=13\n}}\n{{AmFootballScoreSummaryEntry\n| Quarter=3\n| Time=6:52\n| Team=Georgia\n| DrivePlays=4\n| DriveLength=93\n| DriveTime=1:55\n| Type=RecTD\n| Receiver=Mecole Hardman\n| QB=[[Jake Fromm]]\n| yards=80\n| kickresult=good\n| Kicker=Rodrigo Blankenship\n| Visitor=7\n| Home=20\n}}\n{{AmFootballScoreSummaryEntry\n| Quarter=3\n| Time=5:20\n| Team=Alabama\n| DrivePlays=6\n| DriveLength=15\n| DriveTime=1:06\n| Type=FG\n| yards=43\n| Kicker=Andy Pappanastos\n| Visitor=10\n| Home=20\n}}\n{{AmFootballScoreSummaryEntry\n| Quarter=4\n| Time=9:24\n| Team=Alabama\n| DrivePlays=8\n| DriveLength=71\n| DriveTime=2:15\n| Type=FG\n| yards=30\n| Kicker=Andy Pappanastos\n| Visitor=13\n| Home=20\n}}\n{{AmFootballScoreSummaryEntry\n| Quarter=4\n| Time=3:49\n| Team=Alabama\n| DrivePlays=8\n| DriveLength=66\n| DriveTime=3:21\n| Type=RecTD\n| Receiver=[[Calvin Ridley]]\n| QB=Tua Tagovailoa\n| yards=7\n| kickresult=good\n| Kicker=Andy Pappanastos\n| Visitor=20\n| Home=20\n}}\n{{AmFootballScoreSummaryEntry\n| Quarter=OT\n| Time=\n| Team=Georgia\n| DrivePlays=4\n| DriveLength=-9\n| DriveTime=\n| Type=FG\n| yards=51\n| Kicker=Rodrigo Blankenship\n| Visitor=20\n| Home=23\n}}\n{{AmFootballScoreSummaryEntry\n| Quarter=OT\n| Time=\n| Team=Alabama\n| DrivePlays=2\n| DriveLength=25\n| DriveTime=\n| Type=Other\n| Other=DeVonta Smith 41-yard touchdown reception from Tua Tagovailoa\n| Visitor=26\n| Home=23\n}}\n{{AmFootballScoreSummaryEnd|Visitor=26|Home=23}}\n\n===Statistics===\n{{Linescore Amfootball|\n|Road='''No. 4 Crimson Tide'''\n|R1=0|R2=0|R3=10|R4=10|R5=6\n|Home=No. 3 Bulldogs\n|H1=0|H2=13|H3=7|H4=0|H5=3\n}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Statistics !! style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Alabama Crimson Tide}}\"|Alabama !!style=\"{{NCAA secondary color cell|Georgia Bulldogs}}\"|Georgia\n|-\n| First downs || 20 || 22\n|-\n| Plays\u2013yards || 71\u2013371 || 77\u2013365\n|-\n| Rushes\u2013yards || 39\u2013184 || 45\u2013133\n|-\n| Passing yards || 187 || 232\n|-\n| Passing: Comp\u2013Att\u2013Int || 17\u201332\u20131 || 16\u201332\u20132\n|-\n| Time of possession || 26:17 || 33:43\n|-\n| colspan=3 style=\"text-align:center\"| ''Sources'': ''[http://www.espn.com/college-football/matchup?gameId=400953415 ESPN], [http://stats.statbroadcast.com/statmonitr/?id=200140 StatBroadcast]''\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Team !! Category !! Player !! Statistics\n|-\n|rowspan=3 style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Alabama Crimson Tide}}; text-align:center;\"|'''Alabama''' || Passing || [[Tua Tagovailoa]] || 14/24, 166 yds, 3 TD, 1 INT\n|-\n| Rushing || [[Najee Harris]] || 6 car, 64 yds\n|-\n| Receiving || [[Calvin Ridley]] || 4 rec, 32 yds, 1 TD\n|-\n|rowspan=3 style=\"{{NCAA secondary color cell|Georgia Bulldogs}}; text-align:center;\"|'''Georgia''' || Passing || [[Jake Fromm]] || 16/32, 232 yds, 1 TD, 2 INT\n|-\n| Rushing || [[Sony Michel]] || 14 car, 98 yds\n|-\n| Receiving || [[Riley Ridley]] || 6 rec, 82 yds\n|-\n| colspan=4 style=\"text-align:center\"| ''Sources'': ''[http://www.espn.com/college-football/matchup?gameId=400953415 ESPN], [http://stats.statbroadcast.com/statmonitr/?id=200140 StatBroadcast]''\n|}\n\n==Broadcasting==\nThe game was televised nationally by [[ESPN]]. On January 8, 2018, the network announced that its broadcast would feature a live performance by [[Kendrick Lamar]] during halftime. This performance was separate from the event proper at Mercedes-Benz Stadium (which featured a traditional [[halftime show]] with the marching bands of the participating teams), and originated from [[Centennial Olympic Park]].<ref>{{Cite news|title=Kendrick Lamar to Perform at College Football Playoff Title Game|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8071128/kendrick-lamar-college-football-playoff-title-game|work=Billboard|access-date=December 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Other National Championship selections==\n\nFollowing an undefeated season in the [[American Athletic Conference]] and their victory over the [[2017 Auburn Tigers football team|Auburn Tigers]] in the [[2018 Peach Bowl (January)|2018 Peach Bowl]], the [[2017 UCF Knights football team|UCF Knights]] claimed the national championship by virtue of being the only undefeated team in the [[NCAA Division I Football Bowl Subdivision|FBS]] level of college football.<ref>{{cite web|last=Baker|first=Matt|date=January 3, 2018|url=http://www.tampabay.com/blogs/gators/2018/01/03/ucf-is-really-claiming-a-national-championship/ |title=UCF is really claiming a national championship|work=tampabay.com|accessdate=January 7, 2018}}</ref><ref name=final/> Adding to their argument was the fact that Auburn had defeated both Alabama and Georgia during the 2017 regular season. UCF held a victory parade at [[Walt Disney World|Disney World]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.si.com/college-football/2018/01/02/ucf-planning-parade-national-championship-caliber-season|title=UCF Is Having a Parade at Disney World for National Championship Caliber Season|work=Sports Illustrated|first=Khadrice|last=Rollins|date=January 2, 2018|accessdate=January 10, 2018}}</ref> and hung a national championship banner at [[Spectrum Stadium|their stadium]] to celebrate this achievement.<ref>{{Cite news|title=UCF Is Hanging a National Championship Banner at Its Stadium|url=https://www.si.com/college-football/2018/01/03/ucf-football-national-championship-banner|work=Sports Illustrated|first=Dan|last=Gartland|date=January 3, 2018|accessdate=January 10, 2018}}</ref> The school also paid national championship bonuses to all of its assistant coaches, many of whom left UCF after the Peach Bowl to follow head coach [[Scott Frost]] to his new head coaching job at [[Nebraska Cornhuskers football|Nebraska]]; Frost himself (who coached UCF in the game) did not receive such a bonus because he had already been paid all of the bonuses allowed by his UCF contract.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.si.com/college-football/2018/01/03/central-florida-football-coaches-national-championship-bonuses-paid |title=UCF AD Says Coaches Will Be Paid National Championship Bonuses |first=Chris |last=Chavez |website=[[Sports Illustrated|SI.com]] |date=January 3, 2018 |accessdate=January 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe selection committee controversially ranked undefeated UCF 12th at the end of the regular season, below a number of two-loss teams from the [[Power Five conferences]], which left them out of the CFP. The [[AP Poll]] ranked Alabama No. 1 in its final poll, receiving 57 first-place votes, while UCF was ranked No. 6 and received four first-place votes \u2014 the first time in the CFP era that the AP poll did not have a unanimous No. 1 team.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/other/alabama-is-no-1-in-final-ap-poll-for-11th-time-ucf-6th/ar-BBI8Op2 |title=Alabama is No. 1 in final AP poll for 11th time; UCF 6th |publisher=Msn.com |date=January 9, 2018 |accessdate=January 16, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180117012114/https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/other/alabama-is-no-1-in-final-ap-poll-for-11th-time-ucf-6th/ar-BBI8Op2 |archive-date=January 17, 2018 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Additionally, the Knights finished the 2017 football season as the No. 1 team in the [[Colley Matrix]] rankings. The Colley Matrix was used in the past as one input to the BCS computer rankings and is included in a list of historical \"national champion major selections\".<ref>{{cite web|author=Roger Simmons |url=http://www.orlandosentinel.com/sports/from-the-sports-editor/os-sp-ucf-national-champions-colley-matrix-0109-story.html |title=National champions: UCF Knights finish season ranked No. 1 in Colley Matrix |publisher=orlandosentinel.com |date=January 9, 2018 |accessdate=February 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Alabama\u2013Georgia football rivalry]]\n* [[College football national championships in NCAA Division I FBS]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{commons category-inline}}\n\n{{2017 bowl game navbox}}\n{{College Football Playoff navbox}}\n{{Alabama Crimson Tide bowl game navbox}}\n{{Georgia Bulldogs bowl game navbox}}\n{{2017\u201318 NCAA Division I championships navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:College Football Playoff National Championship}}\n[[Category:2017\u201318 NCAA football bowl games]]\n[[Category:2017\u201318 College Football Playoff|National Championship]]\n[[Category:2018 in sports in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Sports competitions in Atlanta]]\n[[Category:American football in Atlanta]]\n[[Category:2018 in Atlanta]]\n[[Category:Alabama Crimson Tide football bowl games]]\n[[Category:Georgia Bulldogs football bowl games]]\n[[Category:January 2018 sports events in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox NCAA football yearly game\n| Game Name          = College Football Playoff National Championship\n| Optional Subheader = 4th College Football Playoff National Championship\n| Title Sponsor      =\n| Image              = CFP Atlanta 2018 logo.svg\n| Image_Size         = 175\n| Image_Upright      =\n| Alt                =\n| Caption            =\n| Date Game Played   = January 8\n| Year Game Played   = 2018\n| Football Season    = 2017\n| Stadium            = [[Mercedes-Benz Stadium]]\n| City               = [[Atlanta|Atlanta, Georgia]]\n| Visitor School     = University of Alabama\n| Visitor Name Short = Alabama\n| Visitor Nickname   = Crimson Tide\n| Visitor Record     = 12-1\n| Visitor Conference = [[American Athletic Conference|SEC]]\n| Visitor AP         = 4\n| Visitor Coaches    = 4\n| Visitor CFP        = 4\n| Visitor Coach      = [[Nick Saban]]\n| Visitor1           = 0\n| Visitor2           = 0\n| Visitor3           = 10\n| Visitor4           = 10\n| Visitor5           = 6\n| Home School        = University of Georgia\n| Home Name Short    = Georgia\n| Home Nickname      = Bulldogs\n| Home Record        = 13\u20131\n| Home Conference    = SEC\n| Home AP            = 3\n| Home Coaches       = 3\n| Home CFP           = 3\n| Home Coach         = [[Kirby Smart]]\n| Home1              = 0\n| Home2              = 13\n| Home3              = 7\n| Home4              = 0\n| Home5              = 3\n| MVP                = Offensive: #13 QB [[Tua Tagovailoa]], Fr. Alabama<br>Defensive: #94 DT [[Daron Payne]], Jr. Alabama\n| Odds               = Alabama by 3.5\n| Anthem             = [[Zac Brown Band]]\n| Referee            = Dan Capron ([[Big Ten Conference|Big Ten]])<ref>{{cite news|last=Kirshner|first=Alex|title=A Big Ten officiating crew is working the all-SEC National Championship|url=https://www.sbnation.com/college-football/2018/1/8/16860896/national-championship-referees-officials-alabama-georgia-2018|publisher=[[SB Nation]]|website=SBNation.com|date=January 8, 2018|access-date=January 8, 2018}}</ref>\n| Halftime           = [[Georgia Redcoat Marching Band]]<br>[[Million Dollar Band (marching band)|Million Dollar Band]]<!-- Do not add Kendrick Lamar. This halftime show is an invention of the broadcast rightsholder and is not the official on-field event. -->\n| Attendance         = 77,430\n| Payout             = \n| US Network         = [[ESPN College Football|ESPN]] and [[ESPN Radio]]\n| US Announcers      = [[Chris Fowler]] (play-by-play)<br>[[Kirk Herbstreit]] (analyst)<br>[[Maria Taylor (analyst)|Maria Taylor]] and [[Tom Rinaldi]] (sideline) (ESPN)<br>[[Sean McDonough]], [[Todd Blackledge]], [[Holly Rowe]] and Ian Fitzsimmons (ESPN Radio)\n| Ratings            = 16.7 (28.44 million viewers)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://espnmediazone.com/us/press-releases/2018/01/epic-college-football-playoff-national-championship-delivers-massive-16-7-overnight-9-year-year/ |title=Epic College Football Playoff National Championship Delivers Massive 16.7 Overnight, Up 9% Year-Over-Year |last=Volner |first=Derek |date=January 9, 2018 |website=www.espnmediazone.com |publisher=ESPN MediaZone |access-date=December 4, 2018}}</ref>\n| Intl Network       = [[ESPN Deportes]]<br>[[ESPN Deportes Radio]]\n| Intl Announcers    = [[Eduardo Varela|Lalo Varela]] and Pablo Viruega (ESPN Deportes)<br>[[Kenneth Garay]] and Sebastian Martinez (ESPN Deportes Radio)\n}}\n\nThe '''2018 College Football Playoff National Championship''' was a [[college football]] [[bowl game]] that determined a [[College football national championships in NCAA Division I FBS|national champion]] in the [[NCAA Division I Football Bowl Subdivision]] for the [[2017 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2017 season]]. The [[2017 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|Alabama Crimson Tide]] defeated the [[2017 Georgia Bulldogs football team|Georgia Bulldogs]] 26\u201323, coming back from a 13\u20130 deficit at [[halftime]] to secure the win in overtime. True freshman quarterback [[Tua Tagovailoa]] and defensive tackle [[Daron Payne]] were respectively named the offensive and defensive players of the game.\n\nThe College Football Playoff selection committee chose the semifinalists following the conclusion of the 2017 regular season. Alabama and Georgia advanced to the national championship after winning the semifinal games hosted by the [[Sugar Bowl]] and [[Rose Bowl Game]] respectively in January 2018. The championship game was played at [[Mercedes-Benz Stadium]] in [[Atlanta|Atlanta, Georgia]] on January 8, 2018.\n\n==Background==\n[[File:Mercedes-Benz Stadium, Jan 2018.jpg|thumb|The 2018 College Football Playoff National Championship took place at [[Mercedes-Benz Stadium]]]]\nThe [[Mercedes-Benz Stadium]] in [[Atlanta]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] was announced as the host site for the fourth College Football National Championship on November 4, 2015.<ref name=\"future sites\">{{cite web|title=Atlanta, Santa Clara and New Orleans land CFP title games for 2018\u201320|author=Alex Scarbrough|publisher=ESPN.com|date=November 4, 2015|accessdate=November 4, 2015|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/id/14052099/atlanta-santa-clara-new-orleans-land-cfp-title-games-2018-20}}</ref>\n\n==2018 College Football Playoff==\n{{2018 College Football Playoff}}\n\nThe [[College Football Playoff]] (CFP) selection committee selected four teams to advance to the playoff: the [[2017 Clemson Tigers football team|Clemson Tigers]], [[2017 Oklahoma Sooners football team|Oklahoma Sooners]], [[2017 Georgia Bulldogs football team|Georgia Bulldogs]], and [[2017 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|Alabama Crimson Tide]].<ref name=final>{{cite web|url=http://collegefootballplayoff.com/documents/2017/12/3/Final_Top_25_College_Football_Playoff_Selection_Day.pdf |title=Selection Committee Rankings: Final Top 25 Rankings |website=College Football Playoff |date=December 3, 2017|access-date=December 3, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Teams==\n===Alabama===\n{{See also|2017 Alabama Crimson Tide football team}}\nThe [[Alabama Crimson Tide football|Alabama Crimson Tide]] defeated the [[Clemson Tigers football|Clemson Tigers]] in the [[2018 Sugar Bowl]] by a score of 24\u20136 to reach the championship game. The Tide had a 12\u20131 season, becoming the SEC West Division co-champions with the [[2017 Auburn Tigers football team|Auburn Tigers]]. The Crimson Tide were coached by [[Nick Saban]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Alabama's Sugar Bowl win against Clemson sets up all-SEC final: Final score, stats, analysis|url=http://www.nola.com/lsu/index.ssf/2018/01/alabama_clemson_sugar_bowl_201.html|publisher=nola.com|date=January 1, 2018|accessdate=January 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Georgia===\n{{See also|2017 Georgia Bulldogs football team}}\nThe [[Georgia Bulldogs football|Georgia Bulldogs]] defeated the [[Oklahoma Sooners football|Oklahoma Sooners]] in the [[2018 Rose Bowl]] by a score of 54\u201348 in double [[overtime (sports)|overtime]] to reach the championship game. The Bulldogs had a 13\u20131 season claiming their 13th [[Southeastern Conference]] (SEC) championship with a rematch victory over the [[Auburn Tigers football|Auburn Tigers]], 28\u20137. The Bulldogs were coached by [[Kirby Smart]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Emerson|first1=Seth|title=Georgia to play for national championship after Rose Bowl win in 2 OT|url=http://www.ajc.com/sports/college-football/georgia-wins-bulldogs-play-for-national-championship-rose-bowl-victory-2ot/0KS2iwglhAtfBE2XXsSQ3N/|publisher=ajc.com|date=January 1, 2018|accessdate=January 2, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Starting lineups==\n[[File:Nick Saban, who is the Alabama team coach, gives interviews and watches all the plays during this important spring scrimmage at University of Alabama, Tuscaloosa, Alabama LCCN2010638313 (cropped).jpg|thumb|left|upright|Alabama head coach [[Nick Saban]]]]\n[[File:Kirby Smart Jan 2018.jpg|thumb|right|upright|Georgia head coach [[Kirby Smart]]]]\n<center>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center; font-size: 95%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:200px;\" style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Alabama Crimson Tide}};\" | Alabama !! Position !! Position !! style=\"{{NCAA secondary color cell|Georgia Bulldogs}};\"|Georgia\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center\"|'''Offense'''\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"#FFCC00\" | [[Calvin Ridley]] 1 || colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\"| [[wide receiver|WR]] || bgcolor=\"#FFCC00\" | [[Javon Wims]] 7\n|-\n| [[Cam Sims]] || colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\"| [[wide receiver|WR]] || bgcolor=\"#FFCC00\" | [[Riley Ridley]] 4\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"#FFCC00\" | [[Jonah Williams]] 1 || colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\"| [[left tackle|LT]] || bgcolor=\"#FFCC00\" | [[Isaiah Wynn]] 1\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"#FFCC00\" | [[Ross Pierschbacher]] 5 || colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\"| [[left guard|LG]] || Kendall Baker\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"#FFCC00\" | [[Bradley Bozeman]] 6 || colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\"| [[center (American football)|C]] || bgcolor=\"#FFCC00\" |  [[Lamont Gaillard]] 6\n|-\n| [[J. C. Hassenauer]] || colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\"| [[right guard|RG]] ||  Ben Cleveland\n|-\n| Matt Womack || colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\"| [[right tackle|RT]] || bgcolor=\"#FFCC00\" | [[Andrew Thomas (American football)|Andrew Thomas]] 1\n|-\n| [[Hale Hentges]] || style=\"text-align:center\"| [[tight end|TE]] || style=\"text-align:center\"| [[Halfback (American football)|TB]] || bgcolor=\"#FFCC00\" | [[Nick Chubb]] 2\n|-\n| [[Robert Foster (American football)|Robert Foster]] || colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\"| WR || bgcolor=\"#FFCC00\" | [[Terry Godwin]] 7\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"#FFCC00\" | [[Jalen Hurts]] 2 || colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\"| [[quarterback|QB]] || bgcolor=\"#FFCC00\" | [[Jake Fromm]] 5\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"#FFCC00\" | [[Damien Harris]] 3 || colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\"| [[running back|RB]] || bgcolor=\"#FFCC00\" | [[Sony Michel]] 1\n|-\n| colspan=\"4\" style=\"text-align:center\"|'''Defense''' \n|-\n| bgcolor=\"#FFCC00\" | [[Da'Shawn Hand]] 4 || colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\"| [[defensive end|DE]] || David Marshall\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"#FFCC00\" | [[Daron Payne]] 1 || colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\"| [[nose guard|NG]] || [[John Atkins (American football)|John Atkins]]\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"#FFCC00\" | [[Isaiah Buggs]] 6 || style=\"text-align:center\"| [[Defensive line|DL]] || style=\"text-align:center\"| [[defensive tackle|DT]] || Tyler Clark\n|-\n| bgcolor=\u201c#FFCC00\u201d | [[Terrell Lewis (American football)|Terrell Lewis]] 3 || style=\"text-align:center\"| [[strongside linebacker|SLB]] || style=\"text-align:center\"| [[Linebacker|LB]] || [[Davin Bellamy]]\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"#FFCC00\" | [[Mack Wilson]] 5 || style=\"text-align:center\"| [[middle linebacker|MLB]] || style=\"text-align:center\"| LB || Reggie Carter \n|-\n| bgcolor=\"#FFCC00\" | [[Rashaan Evans]] 1 || style=\"text-align:center\"| [[weakside linebacker|WLB]] || style=\"text-align:center\"| LB || bgcolor=\"#FFCC00\" | \u2020 [[Roquan Smith]] 1\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"#FFCC00\" | [[Deionte Thompson]] 5 || colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\"| [[Defensive back|DB]] || Malkom Parrish\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"#FFCC00\" | [[Anthony Averett]] 4 || colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\"| [[Cornerback|CB]] || bgcolor=\"#FFCC00\" | [[Deandre Baker]] 1\n|-\n| [[Levi Wallace (American football)|Levi Wallace]] || colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\"| CB || Aaron Davis\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"#FFCC00\" | \u2020 [[Minkah Fitzpatrick]] 1 || style=\"text-align:center\"| [[strong safety|SS]] || style=\"text-align:center\"| [[Safety (gridiron football position)|S]] || Dominick Sanders\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"#FFCC00\" | [[Ronnie Harrison]] 3 || style=\"text-align:center\"| [[free safety|FS]] || style=\"text-align:center\"| CB || J.R Reed\n|-\n| colspan=4 align=center | \u2020 = 2017 All-American\n|-\n| colspan=4 align=center | {{hilite|Selected in an NFL Draft|#FFCC00}}<br>(number corresponds to draft round) \n|}\n</center>\nSource:<ref>{{cite web |url=https://rolltide.com/documents/2018/1/8//2018CFP_GameBook.pdf |title=CFP National Championship Game Book |page=5 |via=rolltide.com |date=January 8, 2018 |accessdate=January 20, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Game summary==\nAfter winning the [[coin toss]], Alabama deferred to the second half and Georgia received the ball to begin the game. After two plays, quarterback [[Jake Fromm]] attempted a pass downfield and was intercepted by Tony Brown. Alabama began their first drive of the game, and, after eleven plays, that drive ended with kicker Andy Pappanastos missing a 40-yard [[field goal]]. The teams each had [[three-and-out]]s for the game's first two [[Punt (gridiron football)|punts]]. During Georgia's ensuing drive, the quarter ended, with no score.<ref name=nytlive>{{cite news|last1=Hoffman|first1=Benjamin|last2=Drape|first2=Joe|last3=Tracy|first3=Marc|title=National Championship Game: Georgia vs. Alabama Live Score|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/01/08/sports/national-championship-game-alabama-georgia.html|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=January 8, 2018|accessdate=January 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAfter a failed third down conversion, on the second play of the second quarter, Georgia kicker [[Rodrigo Blankenship]] hit a 41-yard field goal to open the scoring and put Georgia in the lead by three. Alabama's ensuing drive went nowhere, as they gained four yards on three plays and punted. Georgia took the ball and drove down the field, and found themselves with a first and goal at the Alabama 10-yard-line; the Tide defense held, however, and the Bulldogs settled for a second field goal and took a 6\u20130 lead with just over seven and a half minutes until half. On Alabama's next drive, the Georgia defense held yet again and Alabama's [[JK Scott]] punted for the third time. Just prior to the punt, Georgia wide receiver Javon Wims was shown walking to the locker room, reportedly with a left shoulder injury. Both defenses then forced punts, and Georgia took back over with 1:19 remaining in the half on their own 31-yard-line. Nine plays later, on Alabama's 1-yard-line, [[Mecole Hardman]] took a direct snap, faked a handoff, and ran into the end zone for the game's first touchdown, putting Georgia up 13\u20130 going into [[halftime]].<ref name=nytlive/>\n\nBecause they deferred the coin toss, Alabama received the ball first in the second half. They started their drive on their own 22-yard-line. [[Tua Tagovailoa]], Alabama's backup quarterback, started the second half for the Tide; that drive quickly resulted in a three-and-out. The initial punt was blocked, but an erroneous offside call gave the Tide another chance to punt. Georgia started their drive on their own 36-yard-line, but punted on 4th & 17. Alabama took over on their own 44-yard-line.<ref name=nytlive/> The teams then traded touchdowns on consecutive drives; Alabama scored their first points of the game on a 6-yard pass from Tagovailoa to Ruggs, but Georgia immediately responded with an 80-yard touchdown connection from Fromm to Mecole Hardman, putting Georgia up 20\u20137. On the second play of Alabama's ensuing drive, Tagovailoa, while scrambling to the left, threw into traffic and was intercepted by Georgia's Deandre Baker. Up 13, the Bulldogs took over possession of the ball on Alabama's 39-yard-line. The Tide defense responded immediately, however, as [[Raekwon Davis]] intercepted a Jake Fromm pass on the first play of Georgia's drive, returning the pick to the UGA 40-yard-line. The Tide gained fifteen yards on six plays and kicker Andy Pappanastos avenged his earlier miss with a 43-yard field goal that put Bama within ten. The teams then traded punts. Just prior to Alabama's punt, it was announced that an Alabama defensive back, Kyriq McDonald, had collapsed on the sideline; the situation was described as a \"serious medical emergency\". He was loaded onto a medical stretcher awake and conscious. Georgia could not muster anything on offense that drive, and punted. The fourth quarter saw Tagovailoa lead the Tide to come back and tie the game at 20 with 3:49. With three seconds remaining in the game, Andy Pappanastos missed a potential game-winning 36-yard field goal to the left, sending the game to overtime.<ref name=nytlive/>\n\nIn overtime, Georgia had an unsuccessful drive that resulted in both a three-and-out, and a 13-yard loss sack to Fromm.  Georgia opted to attempt a 51-yard field goal, which they successfully made. On Alabama's first offensive play in overtime, Tagovailoa was sacked for a 16-yard loss, but immediately followed that with a game-winning 41-yard touchdown pass to [[DeVonta Smith]], in a play that has since been called \"2nd and 26\" by fans.<ref name=nytlive/> Tagovailoa was named the offensive player of the game, and [[Daron Payne]] was named the defensive player of the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ncaaf/2018/01/09/cfp-players-game-alabamas-tua-tagovailoa-and-daron-payne/1015832001/|title=CFP players of the game: Alabama's Tua Tagovailoa and Daron Payne|first=A.J.|last=Perez|work=USA Today|date=January 9, 2018|accessdate=January 9, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Scoring summary===\n{{AmFootballScoreSummaryStart|VisitorName=Alabama|HomeName=Georgia|state=}}\n{{AmFootballScoreSummaryEntry\n| Quarter=2\n| Time=14:14\n| Team=Georgia\n| DrivePlays=14\n| DriveLength=55\n| DriveTime=7:40\n| Type=FG\n| yards=41\n| Kicker=[[Rodrigo Blankenship]]\n| Visitor=0\n| Home=3\n}}\n{{AmFootballScoreSummaryEntry\n| Quarter=2\n| Time=7:33\n| Team=Georgia\n| DrivePlays=13\n| DriveLength=70\n| DriveTime=5:19\n| Type=FG\n| yards=27\n| Kicker=Rodrigo Blankenship\n| Visitor=0\n| Home=6\n}}\n{{AmFootballScoreSummaryEntry\n| Quarter=2\n| Time=0:07\n| Team=Georgia\n| DrivePlays=9\n| DriveLength=69\n| DriveTime=1:12\n| Type=RushTD\n| Runner=Mecole Hardman\n| yards=1\n| kickresult=good\n| Kicker=Rodrigo Blankenship\n| Visitor=0\n| Home=13\n}}\n{{AmFootballScoreSummaryEntry\n| Quarter=3\n| Time=8:52\n| Team=Alabama\n| DrivePlays=7\n| DriveLength=56\n| DriveTime=1:59\n| Type=RecTD\n| Receiver=[[Henry Ruggs|Henry Ruggs III]]\n| QB=[[Tua Tagovailoa]]\n| yards=6\n| kickresult=good\n| Kicker=Andy Pappanastos\n| Visitor=7\n| Home=13\n}}\n{{AmFootballScoreSummaryEntry\n| Quarter=3\n| Time=6:52\n| Team=Georgia\n| DrivePlays=4\n| DriveLength=93\n| DriveTime=1:55\n| Type=RecTD\n| Receiver=Mecole Hardman\n| QB=[[Jake Fromm]]\n| yards=80\n| kickresult=good\n| Kicker=Rodrigo Blankenship\n| Visitor=7\n| Home=20\n}}\n{{AmFootballScoreSummaryEntry\n| Quarter=3\n| Time=5:20\n| Team=Alabama\n| DrivePlays=6\n| DriveLength=15\n| DriveTime=1:06\n| Type=FG\n| yards=43\n| Kicker=Andy Pappanastos\n| Visitor=10\n| Home=20\n}}\n{{AmFootballScoreSummaryEntry\n| Quarter=4\n| Time=9:24\n| Team=Alabama\n| DrivePlays=8\n| DriveLength=71\n| DriveTime=2:15\n| Type=FG\n| yards=30\n| Kicker=Andy Pappanastos\n| Visitor=13\n| Home=20\n}}\n{{AmFootballScoreSummaryEntry\n| Quarter=4\n| Time=3:49\n| Team=Alabama\n| DrivePlays=8\n| DriveLength=66\n| DriveTime=3:21\n| Type=RecTD\n| Receiver=[[Calvin Ridley]]\n| QB=Tua Tagovailoa\n| yards=7\n| kickresult=good\n| Kicker=Andy Pappanastos\n| Visitor=20\n| Home=20\n}}\n{{AmFootballScoreSummaryEntry\n| Quarter=OT\n| Time=\n| Team=Georgia\n| DrivePlays=4\n| DriveLength=-9\n| DriveTime=\n| Type=FG\n| yards=51\n| Kicker=Rodrigo Blankenship\n| Visitor=20\n| Home=23\n}}\n{{AmFootballScoreSummaryEntry\n| Quarter=OT\n| Time=\n| Team=Alabama\n| DrivePlays=2\n| DriveLength=25\n| DriveTime=\n| Type=Other\n| Other=DeVonta Smith 41-yard touchdown reception from Tua Tagovailoa\n| Visitor=26\n| Home=23\n}}\n{{AmFootballScoreSummaryEnd|Visitor=26|Home=23}}\n\n===Statistics===\n{{Linescore Amfootball|\n|Road='''No. 4 Crimson Tide'''\n|R1=0|R2=0|R3=10|R4=10|R5=6\n|Home=No. 3 Bulldogs\n|H1=0|H2=13|H3=7|H4=0|H5=3\n}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Statistics !! style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Alabama Crimson Tide}}\"|Alabama !!style=\"{{NCAA secondary color cell|Georgia Bulldogs}}\"|Georgia\n|-\n| First downs || 20 || 22\n|-\n| Plays\u2013yards || 71\u2013371 || 77\u2013365\n|-\n| Rushes\u2013yards || 39\u2013184 || 45\u2013133\n|-\n| Passing yards || 187 || 232\n|-\n| Passing: Comp\u2013Att\u2013Int || 17\u201332\u20131 || 16\u201332\u20132\n|-\n| Time of possession || 26:17 || 33:43\n|-\n| colspan=3 style=\"text-align:center\"| ''Sources'': ''[http://www.espn.com/college-football/matchup?gameId=400953415 ESPN], [http://stats.statbroadcast.com/statmonitr/?id=200140 StatBroadcast]''\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Team !! Category !! Player !! Statistics\n|-\n|rowspan=3 style=\"{{NCAA color cell|Alabama Crimson Tide}}; text-align:center;\"|'''Alabama''' || Passing || [[Tua Tagovailoa]] || 14/24, 166 yds, 3 TD, 1 INT\n|-\n| Rushing || [[Najee Harris]] || 6 car, 64 yds\n|-\n| Receiving || [[Calvin Ridley]] || 4 rec, 32 yds, 1 TD\n|-\n|rowspan=3 style=\"{{NCAA secondary color cell|Georgia Bulldogs}}; text-align:center;\"|'''Georgia''' || Passing || [[Jake Fromm]] || 16/32, 232 yds, 1 TD, 2 INT\n|-\n| Rushing || [[Sony Michel]] || 14 car, 98 yds\n|-\n| Receiving || [[Riley Ridley]] || 6 rec, 82 yds\n|-\n| colspan=4 style=\"text-align:center\"| ''Sources'': ''[http://www.espn.com/college-football/matchup?gameId=400953415 ESPN], [http://stats.statbroadcast.com/statmonitr/?id=200140 StatBroadcast]''\n|}\n\n==Broadcasting==\nThe game was televised nationally by [[ESPN]]. On January 8, 2018, the network announced that its broadcast would feature a live performance by [[Kendrick Lamar]] during halftime. This performance was separate from the event proper at Mercedes-Benz Stadium (which featured a traditional [[halftime show]] with the marching bands of the participating teams), and originated from [[Centennial Olympic Park]].<ref>{{Cite news|title=Kendrick Lamar to Perform at College Football Playoff Title Game|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8071128/kendrick-lamar-college-football-playoff-title-game|work=Billboard|access-date=December 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Other National Championship selections==\n\nFollowing an undefeated season in the [[American Athletic Conference]] and their victory over the [[2017 Auburn Tigers football team|Auburn Tigers]] in the [[2018 Peach Bowl (January)|2018 Peach Bowl]], the [[2017 UCF Knights football team|UCF Knights]] claimed the national championship by virtue of being the only undefeated team in the [[NCAA Division I Football Bowl Subdivision|FBS]] level of college football.<ref>{{cite web|last=Baker|first=Matt|date=January 3, 2018|url=http://www.tampabay.com/blogs/gators/2018/01/03/ucf-is-really-claiming-a-national-championship/ |title=UCF is really claiming a national championship|work=tampabay.com|accessdate=January 7, 2018}}</ref><ref name=final/> Adding to their argument was the fact that Auburn had defeated both Alabama and Georgia during the 2017 regular season. UCF held a victory parade at [[Walt Disney World|Disney World]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.si.com/college-football/2018/01/02/ucf-planning-parade-national-championship-caliber-season|title=UCF Is Having a Parade at Disney World for National Championship Caliber Season|work=Sports Illustrated|first=Khadrice|last=Rollins|date=January 2, 2018|accessdate=January 10, 2018}}</ref> and hung a national championship banner at [[Spectrum Stadium|their stadium]] to celebrate this achievement.<ref>{{Cite news|title=UCF Is Hanging a National Championship Banner at Its Stadium|url=https://www.si.com/college-football/2018/01/03/ucf-football-national-championship-banner|work=Sports Illustrated|first=Dan|last=Gartland|date=January 3, 2018|accessdate=January 10, 2018}}</ref> The school also paid national championship bonuses to all of its assistant coaches, many of whom left UCF after the Peach Bowl to follow head coach [[Scott Frost]] to his new head coaching job at [[Nebraska Cornhuskers football|Nebraska]]; Frost himself (who coached UCF in the game) did not receive such a bonus because he had already been paid all of the bonuses allowed by his UCF contract.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.si.com/college-football/2018/01/03/central-florida-football-coaches-national-championship-bonuses-paid |title=UCF AD Says Coaches Will Be Paid National Championship Bonuses |first=Chris |last=Chavez |website=[[Sports Illustrated|SI.com]] |date=January 3, 2018 |accessdate=January 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe selection committee controversially ranked undefeated UCF 12th at the end of the regular season, below a number of two-loss teams from the [[Power Five conferences]], which left them out of the CFP. The [[AP Poll]] ranked Alabama No. 1 in its final poll, receiving 57 first-place votes, while UCF was ranked No. 6 and received four first-place votes \u2014 the first time in the CFP era that the AP poll did not have a unanimous No. 1 team.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/other/alabama-is-no-1-in-final-ap-poll-for-11th-time-ucf-6th/ar-BBI8Op2 |title=Alabama is No. 1 in final AP poll for 11th time; UCF 6th |publisher=Msn.com |date=January 9, 2018 |accessdate=January 16, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180117012114/https://www.msn.com/en-us/news/other/alabama-is-no-1-in-final-ap-poll-for-11th-time-ucf-6th/ar-BBI8Op2 |archive-date=January 17, 2018 |url-status=dead |df=mdy-all }}</ref> Additionally, the Knights finished the 2017 football season as the No. 1 team in the [[Colley Matrix]] rankings. The Colley Matrix was used in the past as one input to the BCS computer rankings and is included in a list of historical \"national champion major selections\".<ref>{{cite web|author=Roger Simmons |url=http://www.orlandosentinel.com/sports/from-the-sports-editor/os-sp-ucf-national-champions-colley-matrix-0109-story.html |title=National champions: UCF Knights finish season ranked No. 1 in Colley Matrix |publisher=orlandosentinel.com |date=January 9, 2018 |accessdate=February 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Alabama\u2013Georgia football rivalry]]\n* [[College football national championships in NCAA Division I FBS]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{commons category-inline}}\n\n{{2017 bowl game navbox}}\n{{College Football Playoff navbox}}\n{{Alabama Crimson Tide bowl game navbox}}\n{{Georgia Bulldogs bowl game navbox}}\n{{2017\u201318 NCAA Division I championships navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:College Football Playoff National Championship}}\n[[Category:2017\u201318 NCAA football bowl games]]\n[[Category:2017\u201318 College Football Playoff|National Championship]]\n[[Category:2018 in sports in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Sports competitions in Atlanta]]\n[[Category:American football in Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:2018 in Atlanta]]\n[[Category:Alabama Crimson Tide football bowl games]]\n[[Category:Georgia Bulldogs football bowl games]]\n[[Category:January 2018 sports events in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "KingSkyLord", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2018_College_Football_Playoff_National_Championship"}
{"title_page": "Wikipedia administrators", "text_new": "Wikipedia administrators sucking willy on wheels furedai\n\n{{short description|User group on Wikipedia}}\n{{selfref|This is an article about Wikipedia administrators. For Wikipedia's policy page on administrators, see [[Wikipedia:Administrators]].}}\n[[File:Wikipedia Administrator.svg|thumb|Icon that typically represents administrators on Wikipedia]]\n\nOn [[Wikipedia]], trusted users may be appointed as '''administrators''' (also known as admins, sysops, and janitors),<ref name=\"works\">{{cite book|title=How Wikipedia Works|last1=Ayers|first1=Phoebe|last2=Matthews|first2=Charles|last3=Yates|first3=Ben|publisher=[[No Starch Press]]|year=2008|isbn=978-1-59327-176-3|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/howwikipediawork00ayer_0}}</ref>{{rp|327}} following a successful request for adminship. As of {{CURRENTMONTHNAME}} {{CURRENTYEAR}}, there are {{NUMBEROFADMINS}} administrators on the [[English Wikipedia]].<ref name=WP>{{cite web|title=Wikipedia:Administrators|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Administrators|website=Wikipedia|publisher=Wikimedia Foundation|accessdate=29 July 2015}}</ref> Administrators have additional technical privileges compared with other editors.\n\nOn Wikipedia, becoming an admin is often referred to as being \"given [or taking up] the mop\",<ref name=WP /> a term which has also been used elsewhere.<ref name=Mop>{{cite book | title=Taking Up the Mop: Identifying Future Wikipedia Administrators |author1=Burke, Moira |author2=Kraut, Robert | journal=CHI '08 Extended Abstracts on Human Factors in Computing Systems |date=April 2008 | pages=3441\u20133446 | doi=10.1145/1358628.1358871| isbn=978-1-60558-012-8 }}</ref> In 2006, ''[[The New York Times]]'' reported that administrators on Wikipedia, of whom there were then about 1,000, were \"geographically diverse\".<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/06/17/technology/17wiki.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0 | title=Growing Wikipedia Refines Its 'Anyone Can Edit' Policy | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=17 June 2006 | accessdate=23 January 2014 | author=Hafner, Katie}}</ref> In July 2012, it was widely reported that Wikipedia was \"running out of administrators\", because in 2005 and 2006, 40 to 50 people were often appointed administrators each month, but in the first half of 2012, only nine in total were appointed.<ref name=Atlantic /><ref>Further coverage:\n* {{cite web | url=https://www.wired.co.uk/news/archive/2012-07/19/wikipedia-needs-editors | title=Wikipedia might be running out of administrators, figures show | work=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] | date=19 July 2012 | accessdate=24 January 2014 | author=Steadman, Ian|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006110912/http://www.wired.co.uk/news/archive/2012-07/19/wikipedia-needs-editors|archivedate=October 6, 2014}}\n* {{cite web | url=https://www.npr.org/blogs/alltechconsidered/2012/07/19/157056694/as-wikipedia-gets-pickier-editors-become-harder-to-find | title=As Wikipedia Gets Pickier, Editors Become Harder To Find | work=NPR | date=19 July 2012 | accessdate=29 November 2014 | author=Lo Wang, Hansi}}</ref> However, [[Jimmy Wales]], Wikipedia's co-founder, denied that this was a crisis or that Wikipedia was running out of admins, saying, \"The number of admins has been stable for about two years, there's really nothing going on.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-18886752 | title=Jimmy Wales denies Wikipedia admin recruitment crisis | work=[[BBC News]] | date=18 July 2012 | accessdate=24 January 2014 | author=Lee, Dave}}</ref> Wales had previously (in a message sent to the English Wikipedia mailing list on February 11, 2003) stated that being an admin is \"not a big deal\", and that \"It's merely a technical matter that the powers given to sysops are not given out to everyone.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://lists.wikimedia.org/pipermail/wikien-l/2003-February/001149.html | title=Sysop Status | work=EN-I Wikimedia Mailing List | date=11 February 2003 | accessdate=24 January 2014 | author=Wales, Jimmy}}</ref>\n\nIn his book ''[[Wikipedia \u2013 The Missing Manual]]'', John Broughton states that while many people think of administrators on Wikipedia as judges, that is not the purpose of the role.<ref name=Broughton2008 /> Instead, he says, admins usually \"delete pages\" and \"protect pages involved in edit wars\".<ref name=Broughton2008>{{cite book | title=Wikipedia \u2013 The Missing Manual | publisher=[[O'Reilly Media]] | author=Broughton, John | year=2008 | page=199}}</ref>\n\n== Requests for adminship ==\nWhile the first Wikipedia administrators were appointed by [[Jimmy Wales]] in October 2001,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.newyorker.com/archive/2006/07/31/060731fa_fact | title=Know It All | work=[[The New Yorker]] | date=31 July 2006 | accessdate=19 February 2014 | author=Schiff, Stacy}}</ref> administrator privileges on Wikipedia are now granted through a process known as requests for adminship (RfA).<ref name=\"works\" /> Any registered editor may nominate themselves, or may request another editor to do so. The process has been said to be \"akin to putting someone through the Supreme Court\" by [[Andrew Lih]], a scientist and professor who is himself an administrator on the [[English Wikipedia]]. Lih also said, \"It's pretty much a hazing ritual at this point\", in contrast to how the process worked early in Wikipedia's history, when all one had to do to become an admin was \"prove you weren't a bozo\".<ref name=Atlantic /> Candidacy for the role is normally considered only after \"extensive work on the wiki\".<ref name=\"works\" /> While any editor may vote in an RfA, the outcome is not determined by a majority vote, but rather by whether consensus has been reached that the candidate would make a good administrator, a decision that can only be made by a bureaucrat, a Wikipedia editor who is also appointed by the community through a \"request\" process, though the process is much stricter for them than for administrators.<ref>{{cite web|title=Wikipedia:Bureaucrats|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Bureaucrats|website=Wikipedia|publisher=Wikimedia Foundation|accessdate=29 July 2015}}</ref> This may have been implemented as a result of RfAs attracting increasing levels of attention: Stvilia et al. quoted that \"Prior to mid-2005, RfAs typically did not attract much attention. Since then, it has become quite common for RfAs to attract huge numbers of RfA groupies who all support one another\".<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Stvilia |first1=Besiki |last2=Twidale |first2=Michael B. |last3=Smith |first3=Linda C. |last4=Gasser |first4=Les |title=Information quality work organization in wikipedia |doi=10.1002/asi.20813 |journal=[[Journal of the Association for Information Science and Technology]] |volume=59 |issue=6 |pages=983 |year=2008 |citeseerx=10.1.1.163.5109 }}</ref>\n\n== Role ==\nOnce granted administrator privileges, a user has access to additional functions in order to perform certain duties.<ref name=Atlantic>{{cite web | url=https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2012/07/3-charts-that-show-how-wikipedia-is-running-out-of-admins/259829/ | title=3 Charts That Show How Wikipedia Is Running Out of Admins | work=[[The Atlantic]] | date=16 July 2012 | accessdate=23 January 2014 | author=Meyer, Robinson}}</ref> These include \"messy cleanup work\",<ref name=\"works\" /> deletion of articles deemed unsuitable, protecting pages (restricting editing privileges to that page),<ref name=\"wikicollab\">{{cite book|title=Wiki: Web Collaboration|last1=Ebersbach|first1=Anja|last2=Adelung|first2=Andrea|last3=Dueck|first3=Gunter|last4=Glaser|first4=Markus|last5=Heigl|first5=Richard|last6=Warta|first6=Alexander|publisher=Springer|year=2008|isbn=978-3-540-68173-1}}</ref>{{rp|66}} and [[Block (Internet)|blocking]] the accounts of disruptive users.<ref name=\"works\" /><ref name=Atlantic /> Blocking a user must be done according to [[Wikipedia#Policies and laws|Wikipedia's policies]] and a reason must be stated for the block, which will be permanently [[Logfile|logged]] by the software.<ref name=\"works\" />{{rp|401}}<ref name=\"wikicollab\" />{{rp|120}} Use of this privilege to \"gain editing advantages\" is considered inappropriate.<ref name=\"works\" />\n\n== Scientific studies ==\nA scientific paper by researchers from [[Virginia Tech]] and [[Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute]] found that after editors are promoted to administrator status, they often focus more on articles about controversial topics than they did before. The researchers also proposed an alternative method for choosing administrators, in which more weight is given to the votes of experienced editors.<ref>{{cite book | url=http://www.cse.wustl.edu/~sanmay/papers/wiki-cikm.pdf | title=Manipulation Among the Arbiters of Collective Intelligence: How Wikipedia Administrators Mold Public Opinion | author=Das, Sanmay | journal=Proceedings of the 22nd ACM International Conference on Information & Knowledge Management|year=2013| pages=1097\u20131106 | doi=10.1145/2505515.2505566| isbn=978-1-4503-2263-8 }}</ref> Another paper, presented at the 2008 [[Conference on Human Factors in Computing Systems]], analyzed data from all 1,551 requests for adminship from January 2006 to October 2007, with the goal of determining which (if any) of the criteria recommended in Wikipedia's ''Guide to requests for adminship''<ref>See [[Wikipedia:Guide to requests for adminship]].</ref> page were the best predictors of whether the user in question would actually become an admin.<ref name=Mop /> In December 2013, a similar study was published by researchers from the Polish-Japanese Institute of Information Technology in [[Warsaw]], which aimed to model the results of requests for adminship on the [[Polish Wikipedia]] using a model derived from Wikipedia's edit history. They found that they could \"classify the votes in the RfA procedures using this model with an accuracy level that should be sufficient to recommend candidates.\"<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Jankowski-Lorek |first1=Michal |last2=Ostrowski |first2=Lukasz |last3=Turek |first3=Piotr |last4=Wierzbicki |first4=Adam |title=Modeling Wikipedia admin elections using multidimensional behavioral social networks |doi=10.1007/s13278-012-0092-6 |journal=Social Network Analysis and Mining |volume=3 |issue=4 |pages=787 |year=2013 |doi-access=free }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n{{Commons category|Wikipedia administrators}}\n{{Wikipedia}}\n\n[[Category:System administration]]\n[[Category:Wikipedia|Administrators]]\n[[Category:Wikipedians]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|User group on Wikipedia}}\n{{selfref|This is an article about Wikipedia administrators. For Wikipedia's policy page on administrators, see [[Wikipedia:Administrators]].}}\n[[File:Wikipedia Administrator.svg|thumb|Icon that typically represents administrators on Wikipedia]]\n\nOn [[Wikipedia]], trusted users may be appointed as '''administrators''' (also known as admins, sysops, and janitors),<ref name=\"works\">{{cite book|title=How Wikipedia Works|last1=Ayers|first1=Phoebe|last2=Matthews|first2=Charles|last3=Yates|first3=Ben|publisher=[[No Starch Press]]|year=2008|isbn=978-1-59327-176-3|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/howwikipediawork00ayer_0}}</ref>{{rp|327}} following a successful request for adminship. As of {{CURRENTMONTHNAME}} {{CURRENTYEAR}}, there are {{NUMBEROFADMINS}} administrators on the [[English Wikipedia]].<ref name=WP>{{cite web|title=Wikipedia:Administrators|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Administrators|website=Wikipedia|publisher=Wikimedia Foundation|accessdate=29 July 2015}}</ref> Administrators have additional technical privileges compared with other editors.\n\nOn Wikipedia, becoming an admin is often referred to as being \"given [or taking up] the mop\",<ref name=WP /> a term which has also been used elsewhere.<ref name=Mop>{{cite book | title=Taking Up the Mop: Identifying Future Wikipedia Administrators |author1=Burke, Moira |author2=Kraut, Robert | journal=CHI '08 Extended Abstracts on Human Factors in Computing Systems |date=April 2008 | pages=3441\u20133446 | doi=10.1145/1358628.1358871| isbn=978-1-60558-012-8 }}</ref> In 2006, ''[[The New York Times]]'' reported that administrators on Wikipedia, of whom there were then about 1,000, were \"geographically diverse\".<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/06/17/technology/17wiki.html?pagewanted=all&_r=0 | title=Growing Wikipedia Refines Its 'Anyone Can Edit' Policy | work=[[The New York Times]] | date=17 June 2006 | accessdate=23 January 2014 | author=Hafner, Katie}}</ref> In July 2012, it was widely reported that Wikipedia was \"running out of administrators\", because in 2005 and 2006, 40 to 50 people were often appointed administrators each month, but in the first half of 2012, only nine in total were appointed.<ref name=Atlantic /><ref>Further coverage:\n* {{cite web | url=https://www.wired.co.uk/news/archive/2012-07/19/wikipedia-needs-editors | title=Wikipedia might be running out of administrators, figures show | work=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] | date=19 July 2012 | accessdate=24 January 2014 | author=Steadman, Ian|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006110912/http://www.wired.co.uk/news/archive/2012-07/19/wikipedia-needs-editors|archivedate=October 6, 2014}}\n* {{cite web | url=https://www.npr.org/blogs/alltechconsidered/2012/07/19/157056694/as-wikipedia-gets-pickier-editors-become-harder-to-find | title=As Wikipedia Gets Pickier, Editors Become Harder To Find | work=NPR | date=19 July 2012 | accessdate=29 November 2014 | author=Lo Wang, Hansi}}</ref> However, [[Jimmy Wales]], Wikipedia's co-founder, denied that this was a crisis or that Wikipedia was running out of admins, saying, \"The number of admins has been stable for about two years, there's really nothing going on.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-18886752 | title=Jimmy Wales denies Wikipedia admin recruitment crisis | work=[[BBC News]] | date=18 July 2012 | accessdate=24 January 2014 | author=Lee, Dave}}</ref> Wales had previously (in a message sent to the English Wikipedia mailing list on February 11, 2003) stated that being an admin is \"not a big deal\", and that \"It's merely a technical matter that the powers given to sysops are not given out to everyone.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://lists.wikimedia.org/pipermail/wikien-l/2003-February/001149.html | title=Sysop Status | work=EN-I Wikimedia Mailing List | date=11 February 2003 | accessdate=24 January 2014 | author=Wales, Jimmy}}</ref>\n\nIn his book ''[[Wikipedia \u2013 The Missing Manual]]'', John Broughton states that while many people think of administrators on Wikipedia as judges, that is not the purpose of the role.<ref name=Broughton2008 /> Instead, he says, admins usually \"delete pages\" and \"protect pages involved in edit wars\".<ref name=Broughton2008>{{cite book | title=Wikipedia \u2013 The Missing Manual | publisher=[[O'Reilly Media]] | author=Broughton, John | year=2008 | page=199}}</ref>\n\n== Requests for adminship ==\nWhile the first Wikipedia administrators were appointed by [[Jimmy Wales]] in October 2001,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.newyorker.com/archive/2006/07/31/060731fa_fact | title=Know It All | work=[[The New Yorker]] | date=31 July 2006 | accessdate=19 February 2014 | author=Schiff, Stacy}}</ref> administrator privileges on Wikipedia are now granted through a process known as requests for adminship (RfA).<ref name=\"works\" /> Any registered editor may nominate themselves, or may request another editor to do so. The process has been said to be \"akin to putting someone through the Supreme Court\" by [[Andrew Lih]], a scientist and professor who is himself an administrator on the [[English Wikipedia]]. Lih also said, \"It's pretty much a hazing ritual at this point\", in contrast to how the process worked early in Wikipedia's history, when all one had to do to become an admin was \"prove you weren't a bozo\".<ref name=Atlantic /> Candidacy for the role is normally considered only after \"extensive work on the wiki\".<ref name=\"works\" /> While any editor may vote in an RfA, the outcome is not determined by a majority vote, but rather by whether consensus has been reached that the candidate would make a good administrator, a decision that can only be made by a bureaucrat, a Wikipedia editor who is also appointed by the community through a \"request\" process, though the process is much stricter for them than for administrators.<ref>{{cite web|title=Wikipedia:Bureaucrats|url=https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia:Bureaucrats|website=Wikipedia|publisher=Wikimedia Foundation|accessdate=29 July 2015}}</ref> This may have been implemented as a result of RfAs attracting increasing levels of attention: Stvilia et al. quoted that \"Prior to mid-2005, RfAs typically did not attract much attention. Since then, it has become quite common for RfAs to attract huge numbers of RfA groupies who all support one another\".<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Stvilia |first1=Besiki |last2=Twidale |first2=Michael B. |last3=Smith |first3=Linda C. |last4=Gasser |first4=Les |title=Information quality work organization in wikipedia |doi=10.1002/asi.20813 |journal=[[Journal of the Association for Information Science and Technology]] |volume=59 |issue=6 |pages=983 |year=2008 |citeseerx=10.1.1.163.5109 }}</ref>\n\n== Role ==\nOnce granted administrator privileges, a user has access to additional functions in order to perform certain duties.<ref name=Atlantic>{{cite web | url=https://www.theatlantic.com/technology/archive/2012/07/3-charts-that-show-how-wikipedia-is-running-out-of-admins/259829/ | title=3 Charts That Show How Wikipedia Is Running Out of Admins | work=[[The Atlantic]] | date=16 July 2012 | accessdate=23 January 2014 | author=Meyer, Robinson}}</ref> These include \"messy cleanup work\",<ref name=\"works\" /> deletion of articles deemed unsuitable, protecting pages (restricting editing privileges to that page),<ref name=\"wikicollab\">{{cite book|title=Wiki: Web Collaboration|last1=Ebersbach|first1=Anja|last2=Adelung|first2=Andrea|last3=Dueck|first3=Gunter|last4=Glaser|first4=Markus|last5=Heigl|first5=Richard|last6=Warta|first6=Alexander|publisher=Springer|year=2008|isbn=978-3-540-68173-1}}</ref>{{rp|66}} and [[Block (Internet)|blocking]] the accounts of disruptive users.<ref name=\"works\" /><ref name=Atlantic /> Blocking a user must be done according to [[Wikipedia#Policies and laws|Wikipedia's policies]] and a reason must be stated for the block, which will be permanently [[Logfile|logged]] by the software.<ref name=\"works\" />{{rp|401}}<ref name=\"wikicollab\" />{{rp|120}} Use of this privilege to \"gain editing advantages\" is considered inappropriate.<ref name=\"works\" />\n\n== Scientific studies ==\nA scientific paper by researchers from [[Virginia Tech]] and [[Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute]] found that after editors are promoted to administrator status, they often focus more on articles about controversial topics than they did before. The researchers also proposed an alternative method for choosing administrators, in which more weight is given to the votes of experienced editors.<ref>{{cite book | url=http://www.cse.wustl.edu/~sanmay/papers/wiki-cikm.pdf | title=Manipulation Among the Arbiters of Collective Intelligence: How Wikipedia Administrators Mold Public Opinion | author=Das, Sanmay | journal=Proceedings of the 22nd ACM International Conference on Information & Knowledge Management|year=2013| pages=1097\u20131106 | doi=10.1145/2505515.2505566| isbn=978-1-4503-2263-8 }}</ref> Another paper, presented at the 2008 [[Conference on Human Factors in Computing Systems]], analyzed data from all 1,551 requests for adminship from January 2006 to October 2007, with the goal of determining which (if any) of the criteria recommended in Wikipedia's ''Guide to requests for adminship''<ref>See [[Wikipedia:Guide to requests for adminship]].</ref> page were the best predictors of whether the user in question would actually become an admin.<ref name=Mop /> In December 2013, a similar study was published by researchers from the Polish-Japanese Institute of Information Technology in [[Warsaw]], which aimed to model the results of requests for adminship on the [[Polish Wikipedia]] using a model derived from Wikipedia's edit history. They found that they could \"classify the votes in the RfA procedures using this model with an accuracy level that should be sufficient to recommend candidates.\"<ref>{{Cite journal |last1=Jankowski-Lorek |first1=Michal |last2=Ostrowski |first2=Lukasz |last3=Turek |first3=Piotr |last4=Wierzbicki |first4=Adam |title=Modeling Wikipedia admin elections using multidimensional behavioral social networks |doi=10.1007/s13278-012-0092-6 |journal=Social Network Analysis and Mining |volume=3 |issue=4 |pages=787 |year=2013 |doi-access=free }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n{{Commons category|Wikipedia administrators}}\n{{Wikipedia}}\n\n[[Category:System administration]]\n[[Category:Wikipedia|Administrators]]\n[[Category:Wikipedians]]\n", "name_user": "Black VanadaIs Matter", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Undid revision 953895370 byClueBot NG(talk))", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedia_administrators"}
{"title_page": "Sollas", "text_new": "{{For|the geologist|William Johnson Sollas}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox UK place \n | official_name= Sollas\n | gaelic_name= Solas\n | label_position= top\n | static_image_name= Struan cottage - geograph.org.uk - 76275.jpg\n | static_image_caption= Struan cottage. A traditional thatched cottage in Sollas, seen in 2002 and since restored.\n | language= [[Scottish Gaelic]]\n | language1= [[English language|English]]\n | coordinates = {{coord|57.650|-7.345|display=inline,title}}\n | country= Scotland\n | os_grid_reference= NF812747\n | post_town= ISLE OF NORTH UIST\n | postcode_area= HS\n | postcode_district= HS6\n | dial_code= 01876\n | civil_parish= [[North Uist]]\n | constituency_westminster= [[Na h-Eileanan an Iar (UK Parliament constituency)|Na h-Eileanan an Iar]]\n | unitary_scotland= [[Outer Hebrides|Na h-Eileanan Siar]]\n | lieutenancy_scotland= [[Outer Hebrides|Western Isles]]\n | constituency_scottish_parliament= [[Na h-Eileanan an Iar (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Na h-Eileanan an Iar]]\n}}\n\n'''Sollas''' ({{lang-gd|Solas}}) is a small [[crofting]] township on the northern coast of the island of [[North Uist]], [[Scotland]].\n\n==History==\n===The Battle of Sollas===\n\nFrom Sollas, the road that heads towards Bayhead is known as the ''Committee Road''. It is called this as it was organised by a committee charged with providing relief to the [[Highland Potato Famine]] in the 1840s. \nThe Battle of Sollas took place in 1849 during the time of the [[Highland Clearances]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://napier-outerhebrides.blogspot.co.uk/2010/06/north-uist-30-may-1883-john-morrison.html|title=Napier Commission in the Outer Hebrides: North Uist, 30 May 1883 - John Morrison|website=napier-outerhebrides.blogspot.co.uk|access-date=2016-06-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=On the Crofter's Trail|last=Craig|first=David|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=46-8BQAAQBAJ&pg=PT69&lpg=PT69&dq=battle+of+Sollas&source=bl&ots=9QE93w2HRm&sig=me2mqdyd5IvJmR9NOn0DYqDAkmg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjIneDp_bbNAhXqKMAKHWVlBhY4ChDoAQgkMAE#v=onepage&q=battle%2520of%2520Sollas&f=false|title=On the Crofter's Trail|last=Craig|first=David|date=2013-05-13|publisher=Birlinn|isbn=9780857905963|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 1849, Lord Macdonald decided to evict between 600 and 700 people from Sollas. At the time the people were suffering from several years of potato famine. The notices of ejection were served on the tenants on 15 May, 1849. They asked for a delay in order to use their cattle and other effects to their best advantage, but were given no answer. Many of them were soon turned out of their houses and their property seized. It was now the month of July and far too late for them to set out for Canada as the cold winter would be setting in when they arrived, with no means to provide against it and therefore they rebelled. As a result the principal Sheriff-Substitute by the surname of Colqhoun along with his officers and a strong body of police left [[Inverness]] and headed for Sollas on North Uist to eject the tenants from their homes. As the tenant's homes were demolished they began to throw stones at the men carrying out this work who were then driven from the houses and had to retire behind the police for shelter. Volleys of stones and other missiles followed. The police then charged at them in two divisions and there were some cuts and bruises on both sides, but the demolition work then went on uninterrupted. Among the incidents of eviction mentioned by historian [[Alexander Mackenzie (historian)|Alexander Mackenzie]] was that of an old woman who attacked an officer with her stick, knocking off his hat, but then she was carried out by two police officers. Four of them men were later charged with deforcing the officers and were each sentenced to four months imprisonment at the Inverness Court of Justiciary. The following year the whole district were completely cleared of the remaining inhabitants.<ref>{{cite book |last=Mackenzie |first=Alexander |authorlink=Alexander Mackenzie (historian) |year=1914 |title=The History of the Highland Clearances |url=https://archive.org/details/historyofhighlan00mackrich/page/n5/mode/2up  |location=[[Glasgow]] |publisher=P.J. O'Callaghan |pages=[https://archive.org/details/historyofhighlan00mackrich/page/198/mode/2up 198]-201 |accessdate=April 29, 2020}}</ref> \n\nThe Battle of Sollas is featured in the novel ''The False Men'' by Mhairead MacLeod.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Munro|first1=Alistair|last2=(2 August 2017)|title=Traumatic story of the Hebridean Clearances retold|url=https://www.scotsman.com/regions/inverness-highlands-islands/traumatic-story-of-the-hebridean-clearances-retold-1-4520392|publisher=The Scotsman|accessdate=28 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Local amenities== \n[[File:GLAZL GBNHG atSollas.jpg|thumb|left|[[Highland Aviation]] aircraft at Tr\u00e0igh Ear, Sollas, in 2011]]\nToday, the village of Sollas has a local supermarket and the old school building has been turned into a community centre - Taigh Sgire Sholais.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/443672|title=Solas Co-op Store|publisher=[[Geograph Britain and Ireland]]|accessdate=19 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/443676|title=Solas Primary School|publisher=[[Geograph Britain and Ireland]]|accessdate=19 December 2014}}</ref>  Every July, the residents of Sollas host a series of events known as Sollas Week. Sollas is situated in the parish of North Uist,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://canmore.rcahms.gov.uk/en/site/123332/details/north+uist+middlequarter/|title=North Uist, Middlequarter|publisher=[[Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments of Scotland]]|accessdate=19 December 2014}}</ref> and the people are almost entirely [[Protestant]].\n\n==In popular  culture==\n\nSollas beach is featured in the novel ''[[The Chessmen]]'' by [[Peter May (writer)|Peter May]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.visitouterhebrides.co.uk/see-and-do/peter-may-trilogy-sollas-beach-p545001|title=Peter May Trilogy - Sollas Beach|publisher=Visit Outer Hebrides|accessdate=19 December 2014}}</ref> \n\n==Airfield==\n\nNorthern & Scottish Airways inaugurated services to Sollas in February 1936, using beach and the machair (on which it laid out two grass runways, a hangar and a fuel depot). Services continued until [[British European Airways]] retired its [[De Havilland Rapide]]s in the 1950s. The beach at Tr\u00e0igh Ear continues to be used infrequently by light aircraft.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sollas|url=http://www.ukairfieldguide.net/airfields/Sollas|website=UK Airports and Airfields|accessdate=21 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Sollas Airfield|url=http://ukga.com/airfield/sollas|website=UKGA|accessdate=21 November 2016}}</ref> [[Highland Aviation]] uses the beach for its beach landing training course, along with [[Traigh Mh\u00f2r]] beach at [[Barra]] (the site of [[Barra Airport (Scotland)|Barra Airport]]).<ref>{{cite web|title=Beach landing course|url=http://www.highlandaviation.com/courses__prices/beach_landing.asp|website=Highland Aviation|accessdate=21 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[http://canmore.rcahms.gov.uk/en/site/106120/details/north+uist+sollas/ Canmore - North Uist, Sollas, Airfield site record]\n*[http://canmore.rcahms.gov.uk/en/site/214119/details/hermine+solas+north+uist+atlantic/ Canmore - Hermine: Solas, North Uist, Atlantic site record]\n*[http://canmore.rcahms.gov.uk/en/site/279381/details/north+uist+sollas/ Canmore - North Uist, Sollas, Church site record]\n*[http://canmore.rcahms.gov.uk/en/site/10337/details/north+uist+machair+leathann/ Canmore - North Uist, Machair Leathann, Aisled Roundhouse site record]\n*[http://canmore.rcahms.gov.uk/en/site/10327/details/north+uist+skellor+burial+ground/ Canmore - North Uist, Skellor Burial Ground site record]\n\n[[Category:Villages on North Uist]]\n[[Category:Cleared places in the Outer Hebrides]]\n\n\n{{WesternIsles-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{For|the geologist|William Johnson Sollas}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox UK place \n | official_name= Sollas\n | gaelic_name= Solas\n | label_position= top\n | static_image_name= Struan cottage - geograph.org.uk - 76275.jpg\n | static_image_caption= Struan cottage. A traditional thatched cottage in Sollas, seen in 2002 and since restored.\n | language= [[Scottish Gaelic]]\n | language1= [[English language|English]]\n | coordinates = {{coord|57.650|-7.345|display=inline,title}}\n | country= Scotland\n | os_grid_reference= NF812747\n | post_town= ISLE OF NORTH UIST\n | postcode_area= HS\n | postcode_district= HS6\n | dial_code= 01876\n | civil_parish= [[North Uist]]\n | constituency_westminster= [[Na h-Eileanan an Iar (UK Parliament constituency)|Na h-Eileanan an Iar]]\n | unitary_scotland= [[Outer Hebrides|Na h-Eileanan Siar]]\n | lieutenancy_scotland= [[Outer Hebrides|Western Isles]]\n | constituency_scottish_parliament= [[Na h-Eileanan an Iar (Scottish Parliament constituency)|Na h-Eileanan an Iar]]\n}}\n\n'''Sollas''' ({{lang-gd|Solas}}) is a small [[crofting]] township on the northern coast of the island of [[North Uist]], [[Scotland]].\n\n==History==\n===The Battle of Sollas===\n\nFrom Sollas, the road that heads towards Bayhead is known as the ''Committee Road''. It is called this as it was organised by a committee charged with providing relief to the [[Highland Potato Famine]] in the 1840s. \nThe Battle of Sollas took place in 1849 during the time of the [[Highland Clearances]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://napier-outerhebrides.blogspot.co.uk/2010/06/north-uist-30-may-1883-john-morrison.html|title=Napier Commission in the Outer Hebrides: North Uist, 30 May 1883 - John Morrison|website=napier-outerhebrides.blogspot.co.uk|access-date=2016-06-20}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=On the Crofter's Trail|last=Craig|first=David|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=46-8BQAAQBAJ&pg=PT69&lpg=PT69&dq=battle+of+Sollas&source=bl&ots=9QE93w2HRm&sig=me2mqdyd5IvJmR9NOn0DYqDAkmg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjIneDp_bbNAhXqKMAKHWVlBhY4ChDoAQgkMAE#v=onepage&q=battle%2520of%2520Sollas&f=false|title=On the Crofter's Trail|last=Craig|first=David|date=2013-05-13|publisher=Birlinn|isbn=9780857905963|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 1849, Lord Macdonald decided to evict between 600 and 700 people from Sollas. At the time the people were suffering from several years of potato famine. The notices of ejection were served on the tenants on 15 May, 1849. They asked for a delay in order to use their cattle and other effects to their best advantage, but were given no answer. Many of them were soon turned out of their houses and their property seized. It was now the month of July and far too late for them to set out for Canada as the cold winter would be setting in when they arrived, with no means to provide against it and therefore they rebelled. As a result the principal Sheriff-Substitute by the surname of Colqhoun along with his officers and a strong body of police left [[Inverness]] and headed for Sollas on North Uist to eject the tenants from their homes. As the tenant's homes were demolished they began to throw stones at the men carrying out this work who were driven from the houses and had to retire behind the police for shelter. Volleys of stones and other missiles followed. The police then charged at them in two divisions and there were some cuts and bruises on both sides, but the demolition work then went on uninterrupted. Among the incidents of eviction mentioned by historian [[Alexander Mackenzie (historian)|Alexander Mackenzie]] was that of an old woman who attacked an officer with her stick, knocking off his hat, but then she was carried out by two police officers. Four of them men were later charged with deforcing the officers and were each sentenced to four months imprisonment at the Inverness Court of Justiciary. The following year the whole district were completely cleared of the remaining inhabitants.<ref>{{cite book |last=Mackenzie |first=Alexander |authorlink=Alexander Mackenzie (historian) |year=1914 |title=The History of the Highland Clearances |url=https://archive.org/details/historyofhighlan00mackrich/page/n5/mode/2up  |location=[[Glasgow]] |publisher=P.J. O'Callaghan |pages=[https://archive.org/details/historyofhighlan00mackrich/page/198/mode/2up 198]-201 |accessdate=April 29, 2020}}</ref> \n\nThe Battle of Sollas is featured in the novel ''The False Men'' by Mhairead MacLeod.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Munro|first1=Alistair|last2=(2 August 2017)|title=Traumatic story of the Hebridean Clearances retold|url=https://www.scotsman.com/regions/inverness-highlands-islands/traumatic-story-of-the-hebridean-clearances-retold-1-4520392|publisher=The Scotsman|accessdate=28 May 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Local amenities== \n[[File:GLAZL GBNHG atSollas.jpg|thumb|left|[[Highland Aviation]] aircraft at Tr\u00e0igh Ear, Sollas, in 2011]]\nToday, the village of Sollas has a local supermarket and the old school building has been turned into a community centre - Taigh Sgire Sholais.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/443672|title=Solas Co-op Store|publisher=[[Geograph Britain and Ireland]]|accessdate=19 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.geograph.org.uk/photo/443676|title=Solas Primary School|publisher=[[Geograph Britain and Ireland]]|accessdate=19 December 2014}}</ref>  Every July, the residents of Sollas host a series of events known as Sollas Week. Sollas is situated in the parish of North Uist,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://canmore.rcahms.gov.uk/en/site/123332/details/north+uist+middlequarter/|title=North Uist, Middlequarter|publisher=[[Royal Commission on the Ancient and Historical Monuments of Scotland]]|accessdate=19 December 2014}}</ref> and the people are almost entirely [[Protestant]].\n\n==In popular  culture==\n\nSollas beach is featured in the novel ''[[The Chessmen]]'' by [[Peter May (writer)|Peter May]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.visitouterhebrides.co.uk/see-and-do/peter-may-trilogy-sollas-beach-p545001|title=Peter May Trilogy - Sollas Beach|publisher=Visit Outer Hebrides|accessdate=19 December 2014}}</ref> \n\n==Airfield==\n\nNorthern & Scottish Airways inaugurated services to Sollas in February 1936, using beach and the machair (on which it laid out two grass runways, a hangar and a fuel depot). Services continued until [[British European Airways]] retired its [[De Havilland Rapide]]s in the 1950s. The beach at Tr\u00e0igh Ear continues to be used infrequently by light aircraft.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sollas|url=http://www.ukairfieldguide.net/airfields/Sollas|website=UK Airports and Airfields|accessdate=21 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Sollas Airfield|url=http://ukga.com/airfield/sollas|website=UKGA|accessdate=21 November 2016}}</ref> [[Highland Aviation]] uses the beach for its beach landing training course, along with [[Traigh Mh\u00f2r]] beach at [[Barra]] (the site of [[Barra Airport (Scotland)|Barra Airport]]).<ref>{{cite web|title=Beach landing course|url=http://www.highlandaviation.com/courses__prices/beach_landing.asp|website=Highland Aviation|accessdate=21 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*[http://canmore.rcahms.gov.uk/en/site/106120/details/north+uist+sollas/ Canmore - North Uist, Sollas, Airfield site record]\n*[http://canmore.rcahms.gov.uk/en/site/214119/details/hermine+solas+north+uist+atlantic/ Canmore - Hermine: Solas, North Uist, Atlantic site record]\n*[http://canmore.rcahms.gov.uk/en/site/279381/details/north+uist+sollas/ Canmore - North Uist, Sollas, Church site record]\n*[http://canmore.rcahms.gov.uk/en/site/10337/details/north+uist+machair+leathann/ Canmore - North Uist, Machair Leathann, Aisled Roundhouse site record]\n*[http://canmore.rcahms.gov.uk/en/site/10327/details/north+uist+skellor+burial+ground/ Canmore - North Uist, Skellor Burial Ground site record]\n\n[[Category:Villages on North Uist]]\n[[Category:Cleared places in the Outer Hebrides]]\n\n\n{{WesternIsles-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "QuintusPetillius", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sollas"}
{"title_page": "Claas Lexion", "text_new": "[[File:Claas-Lexion-570-2.jpg|thumb|Claas-Lexion-570-2]]\n'''Claas Lexion''' is a series of [[combine harvester]]s, manufactured by [[Claas]] in [[Harsewinkel]]. An American version called '''Lexion''' was produced by Claas Omaha Inc. in the United States.\n\n== History ==\nThe Lexion was presented in 1995. The first model was the Lexion 480. It has a harvesting capacity of 40&nbsp;t of grain per hour and was at that time the most powerful combine harvester in the world.<ref>{{cite web|title=History of Claas|url=http://www.claas-group.com/cc/servlet/generator/cl-gr/en/company/history/milestones/start,bpSite=35108.html|publisher=Claas|accessdate=10 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130813082617/http://www.claas-group.com/cc/servlet/generator/cl-gr/en/company/history/milestones/start%2CbpSite%3D35108.html|archivedate=13 August 2013}}</ref> The Lexion 480 had the same accelerator drum in front the threshing drum as the Claas Mega, but it came with a bigger threshing drum (600&nbsp;mm diameter and 1700&nbsp;mm width instead of 450&nbsp;mm diameter and 1580&nbsp;mm width). Instead of the straw walkers, the Lexion 480 had two separation rotors installed. As a result, the unit ran smoothly and the throughput was much higher than in a conventional straw-walker machine.<ref>{{cite web|title=Modern Testing Technology for CLAAS Combine Harvesters|url=http://www.hoerbiger.com/en-534/pages/236|publisher=Hoerbiger|accessdate=10 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1999, [[Claas]] worked with the US agricultural and construction machinery manufacturer [[Caterpillar Inc.|Caterpillar]] and sold the Lexion combines in North America under the CAT brand. In 2002, Claas took over 50% of the joint venture with Caterpillar and the combine harvester production in the United States. The harvesters produced there were then still marketed as CAT Lexion.<ref>{{cite book|last=Orlemann|first=Eric C.|title=Caterpillar chronicle : the history of the world's greatest earthmovers|year=2000|publisher=Motorbooks International|location=St. Paul, Minn.|isbn=0760306672|page=149}}</ref>\n\nAt the 2005 Agritechnica exhibition, Claas presented the Lexion 600, with a cutting width of up to 12 m, a grain tank capacity of 12,000 liters and a performance up to 60,000&nbsp;kg per hour.<ref>{{cite web|title=Claas: High-horsepower Xerions revealed at Agritechnica|url=http://www.wnif.co.uk/articles/333/1/Claas-High-horsepower-Xerions-revealed-at-Agritechnica/Page1.html|publisher=Whats new in Agriculture|accessdate=10 August 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130813015230/http://www.wnif.co.uk/articles/333/1/Claas-High-horsepower-Xerions-revealed-at-Agritechnica/Page1.html|archive-date=13 August 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> This was again the most powerful combine harvester in the world. In 2010, Claas presented the Lexion 700. In 2013, Claas introduced new emission standards (Tier 4).<ref>{{cite web|title=New CLAAS LEXION and ARION make Ploughing Match debut|url=http://www.machineshift.com/blog/?p=1755|publisher=Machine Shift|accessdate=10 August 2013}}</ref> The Lexion 8900 released in 2019 has 581&nbsp;kW MAN D42 engine that matches the [[Fendt#Combines|Fendt Ideal]] 10,000&nbsp;kg class 10 combine released in 2020.<ref name=\"uk\">{{cite web|URL=https://www.fwi.co.uk/machinery/harvest-equipment/combines/claas-launches-biggest-ever-lexion-combine-the-790hp-8900 |title=Video: Claas launches biggest-ever Lexion combine \u2013 the 790hp 8900 |publisher=Farmers Weekly|date=24 July 2019 |author=Adam Clarke |accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Lexion series ==\n\n*400 series (two separation rotors)\n*500 series (six straw walkers)\n*600 series (six straw walkers)\n*700 series (two separation rotors)\n*5000 series (five straw walkers)\n*6000 series (six straw walkers)\n*7000 series (two separation rotors)\n*8000 series (two separation rotors)\n\n== External links ==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Claas]]\n[[Category: combine harvesters]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Claas-Lexion-570-2.jpg|thumb|Claas-Lexion-570-2]]\n'''Claas Lexion''' is a series of [[combine harvester]]s, manufactured by [[Claas]] in [[Harsewinkel]]. An American version called '''Lexion''' was produced by Claas Omaha Inc. in the United States.\n\n== History ==\nThe Lexion was presented in 1995. The first model was the Lexion 480. It has a harvesting capacity of 40&nbsp;t of grain per hour and was at that time the most powerful combine harvester in the world.<ref>{{cite web|title=History of Claas|url=http://www.claas-group.com/cc/servlet/generator/cl-gr/en/company/history/milestones/start,bpSite=35108.html|publisher=Claas|accessdate=10 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130813082617/http://www.claas-group.com/cc/servlet/generator/cl-gr/en/company/history/milestones/start%2CbpSite%3D35108.html|archivedate=13 August 2013}}</ref> The Lexion 480 had the same accelerator drum in front the threshing drum as the Claas Mega, but it came with a bigger threshing drum (600&nbsp;mm diameter and 1700&nbsp;mm width instead of 450&nbsp;mm diameter and 1580&nbsp;mm width). Instead of the straw walkers, the Lexion 480 had two separation rotors installed. As a result, the unit ran smoothly and the throughput was much higher than in a conventional straw-walker machine.<ref>{{cite web|title=Modern Testing Technology for CLAAS Combine Harvesters|url=http://www.hoerbiger.com/en-534/pages/236|publisher=Hoerbiger|accessdate=10 August 2013}}</ref>\n\nFrom 1999, [[Claas]] worked with the US agricultural and construction machinery manufacturer [[Caterpillar Inc.|Caterpillar]] and sold the Lexion combines in North America under the CAT brand. In 2002, Claas took over 50% of the joint venture with Caterpillar and the combine harvester production in the United States. The harvesters produced there were then still marketed as CAT Lexion.<ref>{{cite book|last=Orlemann|first=Eric C.|title=Caterpillar chronicle : the history of the world's greatest earthmovers|year=2000|publisher=Motorbooks International|location=St. Paul, Minn.|isbn=0760306672|page=149}}</ref>\n\nAt the 2005 Agritechnica exhibition, Claas presented the Lexion 600, with a cutting width of up to 12 m, a grain tank capacity of 12,000 liters and a performance up to 60,000&nbsp;kg per hour.<ref>{{cite web|title=Claas: High-horsepower Xerions revealed at Agritechnica|url=http://www.wnif.co.uk/articles/333/1/Claas-High-horsepower-Xerions-revealed-at-Agritechnica/Page1.html|publisher=Whats new in Agriculture|accessdate=10 August 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130813015230/http://www.wnif.co.uk/articles/333/1/Claas-High-horsepower-Xerions-revealed-at-Agritechnica/Page1.html|archive-date=13 August 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> This was again the most powerful combine harvester in the world. In 2010, Claas presented the Lexion 700. In 2013, Claas introduced new emission standards (Tier 4).<ref>{{cite web|title=New CLAAS LEXION and ARION make Ploughing Match debut|url=http://www.machineshift.com/blog/?p=1755|publisher=Machine Shift|accessdate=10 August 2013}}</ref> The Lexion 8900 released in 2019 has 581&nbsp;kW MAN D42 engine that matches the [[Fendt#Combines|Fendt Ideal]] 10,000&nbsp;kg class 10 combine released in 2020.<ref name=\"uk\">{{cite web|URL=https://www.fwi.co.uk/machinery/harvest-equipment/combines/claas-launches-biggest-ever-lexion-combine-the-790hp-8900 |title=Video: Claas launches biggest-ever Lexion combine \u2013 the 790hp 8900 |publisher=Farmers Weekly|date=24 July 2019 |author=Adam Clarke |accessdate=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Lexion series ==\n\n*400 series (two seperation rotors)\n*500 series (six straw walkers)\n*600 series (six straw walkers)\n*700 series (two seperation rotors)\n*5000 series (five straw walkers)\n*6000 series (six straw walkers)\n*7000 series (two seperation rotors)\n*8000 series (two seperation rotors)\n\n== External links ==\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Claas]]\n[[Category: combine harvesters]]\n", "name_user": "Cyfal", "label": "safe", "comment": "spelling (Wikipedia:Typo Team)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Claas_Lexion"}
{"title_page": "Alexandros Paschalakis", "text_new": "{{short description|Greek goalkeeper}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Alexandros Paschalakis\n| image = Paok-spartak (14).jpg \n| caption     = Paschalakis playing with [[PAOK FC|PAOK]] in 2018\n| fullname = Alexandros Paschalakis\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1989|7|28|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Athens]], Greece\n| height = {{height|meters=1.98}}\n| position =  [[Goalkeeper (association football)|Goalkeeper]]\n| currentclub = [[PAOK FC|PAOK]] \n| clubnumber = 31\n| youthyears1 = 2003\u20132004\n| youthclubs1 = [[AEK Athens F.C.|AEK Athens]]\n| youthyears2 = 2004\u20132005\n| youthclubs2 = [[Olympiacos F.C.|Olympiacos]]\n| youthyears3 = 2005\u20132006\n| youthclubs3 = [[GS Ilioupolis|Ilioupoli]] \n| years1 = 2006\u20132008\n| clubs1 = [[GS Ilioupolis|Ilioupoli]]           \n| caps1 = 0 \n| goals1 = 0\n| years2 = 2008\u20132012 \n| clubs2 = [[Levadiakos F.C.|Levadiakos]]       \n| caps2 = 2\n| goals2 = 0\n| years3 = 2012\u20132013 \n| clubs3 = [[PAEEK]]                  \n| caps3 = 23\n| goals3 = 0\n| years4 = 2013\u20132016 \n| clubs4=[[Panthrakikos F.C.|Panthrakikos]]     \n| caps4= 18 \n| goals4= 0\n| years5 = 2016\u20132017   \n| clubs5=[[PAS Giannina F.C.|PAS Giannina]]     \n| caps5= 27\n| goals5= 0\n| years6 = 2017\u2013\n| clubs6 = [[PAOK FC|PAOK]]\n| caps6 = 53\n| goals6 = 57\n| nationalyears1 = 2019\u2013\n|  nationalteam1 = [[Greece national football team|Greece]]\n|  nationalcaps1 = 3\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n|medaltemplates =\n| pcupdate = 1 March 2020\n| ntupdate = 15 October 2019\n}}\n\n'''Alexandros Paschalakis''' (Alexander Little Easter) ({{lang-el|\u0391\u03bb\u03ad\u03be\u03b1\u03bd\u03b4\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2 \u03a0\u03b1\u03c3\u03c7\u03b1\u03bb\u03ac\u03ba\u03b7\u03c2}}; born 28 July 1989) is a Greek professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]] for [[PAOK FC|PAOK]] and the [[Greece national football team|Greece national team]].\n\n==Club career==\n===Early career===\nHe started playing football in Terpsithea. He was at the youth team of [[AEK Athens F.C.|AEK]] for a year and then at the youth team of [[Olympiacos F.C.|Olympiakos]] for 2 years (2003\u20132005). He moved to the team of [[GS Ilioupolis|Ilioupoli]]. At the age of 17 he transferred to the youth team of [[Galatasaray S.K. (football)|Galatasaray]] but he couldn't sign a contract due to restrictions on the number of foreign players.\n\nHe signed for [[Levadiakos F.C.|Levadiakos]] in the summer of 2008. He signed for [[PAEEK]] in the summer of 2012. [[Akhisar Belediyespor|Akhisar]] was interested in Paschalakis but he didn't want to move there.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sport24.gr/football/omades/PasGiannina/air-pasxalakhs.4564593.html|title=Air \u03a0\u03b1\u03c3\u03c7\u03b1\u03bb\u03ac\u03ba\u03b7\u03c2|date=8 March 2017|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gazzetta.gr/match-review/article/1031257/taxidi-toy-kanithares-tis-ipeiroy-mehri-tin-kataxiosi|title=\u03a4\u03bf \u03c4\u03b1\u03be\u03af\u03b4\u03b9 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5... \u039a\u03b1\u03bd\u03b9\u03b8\u03ac\u03c1\u03b5\u03c2 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u0397\u03c0\u03b5\u03af\u03c1\u03bf\u03c5, \u03bc\u03ad\u03c7\u03c1\u03b9 \u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u03ba\u03b1\u03c4\u03b1\u03be\u03af\u03c9\u03c3\u03b7!|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> After returning to Greece and spending six months in limbo, he signed for Panthrakikos on January 2014, but played just 13 matches until January 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.novasports.gr/podosfairo/ellada/super-league/article/67283/anakoinose-ton-pashalaki-o-panthrakikos/|title=\u0391\u03bd\u03b1\u03ba\u03bf\u03af\u03bd\u03c9\u03c3\u03b5 \u03c4\u03bf\u03bd \u03a0\u03b1\u03c3\u03c7\u03b1\u03bb\u03ac\u03ba\u03b7 \u03bf \u03a0\u03b1\u03bd\u03b8\u03c1\u03b1\u03ba\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc\u03c2|date=8 January 2014|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nHe signed for [[PAS Giannina F.C.|PAS Giannina]] on 26 January 2016, to replace [[Markos Vellidis]]' transfer to [[PAOK]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pasgiannina.gr/articles/anakoinose_pae_pas_giannina_1966_62|title=\u0391\u03bd\u03b1\u03ba\u03bf\u03af\u03bd\u03c9\u03c3\u03b7 \u03a0\u0391\u0395 \u03a0\u0391\u03a3 \u0393\u0399\u0391\u039d\u039d\u0399\u039d\u0391 1966|date=26 January 2016|website=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170729223350/http://www.pasgiannina.gr/articles/anakoinose_pae_pas_giannina_1966_62|archive-date=29 July 2017|access-date=|url-status=dead}}</ref> He didn't play at all in his first six months in Giannina. On 25 July 2017, the 28-year-old goalkeeper that was bound by a contract to the club until the summer of 2018, had made an appeal due to a delay in his annual salary. The Athenian goalie had an outstanding season playing in 27 games, out of which four in [[UEFA Europa League]]. [[PAOK]], along with [[Asteras Tripoli]] and [[Panathinaikos]] expressed interest in his acquisition, having 9 clean sheets.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sport24.gr/football/omades/PasGiannina/prosfygh-kata-toy-pas-giannina-o-pasxalakhs.4780323.html |title=\u03a0\u03c1\u03bf\u03c3\u03c6\u03c5\u03b3\u03ae \u03ba\u03b1\u03c4\u03ac \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u03a0\u0391\u03a3 \u0393\u03b9\u03ac\u03bd\u03bd\u03b9\u03bd\u03b1 \u03bf \u03a0\u03b1\u03c3\u03c7\u03b1\u03bb\u03ac\u03ba\u03b7\u03c2 |date=25 July 2017|publisher=sport24.gr |access-date=29 July 2017}}</ref> On 1 August, Paschalakis was released from [[PAS Giannina F.C.|PAS Giannina]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sport24.gr/football/omades/PasGiannina/symvivastikh-lush-pas-me-pasxalakh-poy-menei-eleutheros.4788506.html |title=\u03a3\u03c5\u03bc\u03b2\u03b9\u03b2\u03b1\u03c3\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae \u03bb\u03cd\u03c3\u03b7 \u03a0\u0391\u03a3 \u03bc\u03b5 \u03a0\u03b1\u03c3\u03c7\u03b1\u03bb\u03ac\u03ba\u03b7 \u03c0\u03bf\u03c5 \u03bc\u03ad\u03bd\u03b5\u03b9 \u03b5\u03bb\u03b5\u03cd\u03b8\u03b5\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2 |date=1 August 2017|publisher=sport24.gr }}</ref>\n\n===PAOK===\nOn 7 August 2017, he signed a year contract with [[PAOK FC|PAOK]] for an undisclosed fee.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.paokfc.gr/nea/20170807-ston-paok-o-paschalakis/|title=\u03a3\u03c4\u03bf\u03bd \u03a0\u0391\u039f\u039a \u03bf \u03a0\u03b1\u03c3\u03c7\u03b1\u03bb\u03ac\u03ba\u03b7\u03c2|date=7 August 2017|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> On 2 December 2017, he made his debut in a 3\u20130 away win against [[Xanthi F.C.|Xanthi]] A day later he renewed his contract with the club till the summer of 2020. The 28-year-old goalkeeper has increased his earnings and the release clause will be set in the region of \u20ac5 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sport24.gr/football/omades/Paok/ananewse-me-rhtra-5-ekat-eyrw-o-pasxalakhs.4967547.html |title=\u0391\u03bd\u03b1\u03bd\u03ad\u03c9\u03c3\u03b5 \u03bc\u03b5 \u03c1\u03ae\u03c4\u03c1\u03b1 5 \u03b5\u03ba\u03b1\u03c4. \u03b5\u03c5\u03c1\u03ce \u03bf \u03a0\u03b1\u03c3\u03c7\u03b1\u03bb\u03ac\u03ba\u03b7\u03c2! |date=3 December 2017|publisher=sport24.gr }}</ref>\n\nIt was initially planned that he would be back-up to Argentinian [[Rodrigo Rey]], but since head coach [[Razvan Lucescu]] gave him a chance, Paschalakis has made himself PAOK's starter. As of 4 February 2018, Paschalakis holds PAOK's record for most consecutive minutes without conceding, with 971 excluding stoppage time (1008 in total), before conceding in a 1\u20133 away win over PAS Giannina,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sport24.gr/football/ellada/SuperLeague/aeras-o-paok-3-1-ton-pas-sta-giannina.5061854.html|title=\u0391\u03ad\u03c1\u03b1\u03c2 \u03bf \u03a0\u0391\u039f\u039a, 3\u20131 \u03c4\u03bf\u03bd \u03a0\u0391\u03a3 \u03c3\u03c4\u03b1 \u0393\u03b9\u03ac\u03bd\u03bd\u03b9\u03bd\u03b1|access-date=8 February 2018|language=en}}</ref> to surpass current runner-up [[Kostas Chalkias]] with 859 min. Unsurprisingly, PAOK boast the [[Greek Super League|Superleague]]'s tightest defence with seven goals conceded in nineteen matches, a statistic which is largely down to Paschalakis' superb performances between the sticks.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sport24.gr/Files/o-pasxalakhs-grafei-istoria-sthn-estia-toy-paok.5051697.html|title=\u039f \u03a0\u03b1\u03c3\u03c7\u03b1\u03bb\u03ac\u03ba\u03b7\u03c2 \u03b3\u03c1\u03ac\u03c6\u03b5\u03b9 \u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03c1\u03af\u03b1 \u03c3\u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u03b5\u03c3\u03c4\u03af\u03b1 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u03a0\u0391\u039f\u039a|access-date=30 January 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 August 2018, Paschalakis saves second-half [[Quincy Promes]] penalty in a 3\u20132 home win game for [[UEFA Champions League|UEFA Champions League Third qualifying round, 1st leg]] against [[FC Spartak Moscow|Spartak Moskva]], helping his club to maintain the win.<ref>{{cite news|title=\u039c\u03b5\u03b3\u03ac\u03bb\u03b7 \u0391\u03bd\u03b1\u03c4\u03c1\u03bf\u03c0\u03ae \u03b3\u03b9\u03b1 \u03c4\u03bf\u03bd \u03a0\u0391\u039f\u039a 3\u20132 \u03b5\u03c0\u03af \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u03a3\u03c0\u03ac\u03c1\u03c4\u03b1\u03ba \u03c3\u03c4\u03b7 \u03a4\u03bf\u03cd\u03bc\u03c0\u03b1 |url=https://www.voria.gr/article/live-apo-tin-toumpa-i-megali-anametrisi-paok-vs-spartak |publisher=voria.gr|date=8 August 2018}}</ref>\nIn the first half of the [[2018\u201319 Superleague Greece|2018\u201319 season]] Paschalakis played every minute of domestic championship action, conceding a mere six goals in 15 matches while tallying an impressive nine clean sheets. On 17 January 2019, Paschalakis was awarded a new contract with PAOK through to 2022, and assuming he continues keeping the opponents off the scoreboard, PAOK will surely win the Greek championship for the first time in 34 years.<ref>{{cite news|title=\u03a0\u03b1\u03c3\u03c7\u03b1\u03bb\u03ac\u03ba\u03b7\u03c2 \u03c9\u03c2 \u03c4\u03bf 2022 \u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03bd \u03a0\u0391\u039f\u039a! |url=http://www.gazzetta.gr/football/superleague/article/1314678/pashalakis-os-2022-ston-paok |publisher=gazzetta.gr|date=17 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 April 2019, made a number of saves in a semifinal second leg [[Greek Cup]] game against [[Asteras Tripolis]], helping PAOK's title defence of the Greek Cup, as the newly crowned [[Super League]] champions secured a 0\u20130 draw in Tripoli to progress 2\u20130 on aggregate.  PAOK for the third consecutive season will meet [[AEK Athens]] in the Greek Cup final.<ref>{{cite news|title=\u0391\u03c3\u03c4\u03ad\u03c1\u03b1\u03c2 \u03a4\u03c1\u03af\u03c0\u03bf\u03bb\u03b7\u03c2 \u2013 \u03a0\u0391\u039f\u039a 0\u20130 |url=http://www.gazzetta.gr/football/kypello-elladas/article/1349470/asteras-tripolis-paok-0-0 |publisher=gazzetta.gr|date=25 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nOn 5 October 2018 Greece coach [[Michael Skibbe]] called up goalie Alexandros Paschalakis for upcoming [[2018\u201319 UEFA Nations League]] matches against [[Hungary national football team|Hungary]] and [[finland national football team|Finland]] for [[UEFA Nations League]]. ''\"All players dream of someday representing their country and I am happy for this opportunity. I waited for a long time for this call,\"'' said Paschalakis.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.sport24.gr/football/omades/Paok/pasxalakhs-perimena-polu-kairo-thn-klhsh-sthn-ethnikh-ellados.5329166.html |title=\u03a0\u03b1\u03c3\u03c7\u03b1\u03bb\u03ac\u03ba\u03b7\u03c2: \"\u03a0\u03b5\u03c1\u03af\u03bc\u03b5\u03bd\u03b1 \u03c0\u03bf\u03bb\u03cd \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9\u03c1\u03cc \u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u03ba\u03bb\u03ae\u03c3\u03b7 \u03c3\u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u0395\u03b8\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03ac\u03b4\u03bf\u03c2\"|publisher= sport24.gr| language=el|date=5 October 2018}}</ref> On 30 May 2019, he made his debut in a 2\u20131 [[Exhibition match|friendly game]] away loss against [[Turkey national football team|Turkey]].\n\n==Career statistics ==\n{{updated|4 March 2020}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Club\n!rowspan=2|Season\n! colspan=\"3\" |[[Championship]]\n!colspan=2|[[Cup]]\n!colspan=2|[[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]]\n!colspan=2|[[UEFA Europa League|Europa League]]\n!colspan=2|Total\n|-\n!Division\n!Apps\n!Goals\n!Apps\n!Goals\n!Apps\n!Goals\n!Apps\n!Goals\n!Apps\n!Goals\n|-\n| rowspan=3 |[[Panthrakikos F.C.|Panthrakikos]]\n|[[2013\u201314 Superleague Greece|2013\u201314]]\n| rowspan=\"3\" |[[Super League Greece]]\n|5||0||0||0||0||0||0||0||5||0 \n|-\n|[[2014\u201315 Superleague Greece|2014\u201315]]\n|4||0||3||0||0||0||0||0||7||0 \n|-\n|[[2015\u201316 Superleague Greece|2015\u201316]]\n|4||0||2||0||0||0||0||0||6||0 \n|-\n| rowspan=1 |[[PAS Giannina F.C.|PAS Giannina]]\n|[[2016\u201317 Superleague Greece|2016\u201317]]\n|[[Super League Greece]]\n|20||0||3||0||0||0||4||0||27||0 \n|-\n| rowspan=3 |[[PAOK F.C.|PAOK]]\n|[[2017\u201318 Superleague Greece|2017\u201318]]\n| rowspan=\"3\" |[[Super League Greece]]\n|17||0||7||0||0||0||0||0||25||0 \n|-\n|[[2018\u201319 Superleague Greece|2018\u201319]]\n|30||0||6||0||6||0||6||0||48||0 \n|-\n|[[2019\u201320 Superleague Greece|2019\u201320]]\n|6||0||4||0||2||0||2||0||14||0 \n|-\n! colspan=\"3\" | Career totals\n!86!!0!!25!!0!!8!!0!!12!!0!!131!!0\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n\n===Club===\n;PAOK\n*[[Super League Greece]]: [[2018\u201319 Superleague Greece|2018\u201319]]\n*[[Greek Football Cup|Greek Cup]]: [[2017\u201318 Greek Football Cup|2017\u201318]],<ref>https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2018/02/28/greece/cup/panionios-nfc/paok-fc/2744640/</ref> [[2018\u201319 Greek Football Cup|2018\u201319]]\n\n===Individual===\n*[[Greek football PSAP awards#Superleague Greece Awards|Super League Greece Greek Best Goalkeeper of the Year]]: [[2018\u201319 Superleague Greece|2018\u201319]]\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*{{soccerway|alexandros-paschalakis/67710}}\n*{{UEFA player}}\n*{{NFT player|74367}}\n\n{{PAOK F.C. squad}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Awards\n| bg = gold\n| fg = navy\n| list1 = \n{{2018\u201319 Super League Greece Team of the Year}}\n{{Super League Greece Goalkeeper of the Year}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Paschalakis, Alexandros}}\n[[Category:1989 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Greek footballers]]\n[[Category:Greece international footballers]]\n[[Category:Super League Greece players]]\n[[Category:Levadiakos F.C. players]]\n[[Category:PAEEK players]]\n[[Category:Panthrakikos F.C. players]]\n[[Category:PAS Giannina F.C. players]]\n[[Category:PAOK FC players]]\n[[Category:Association football goalkeepers]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Athens]]\n[[Category:Cypriot Second Division players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Cyprus]]\n[[Category:Greek expatriate footballers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Greek goalkeeper}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Alexandros Paschalakis\n| image = Paok-spartak (14).jpg \n| caption     = Paschalakis playing with [[PAOK FC|PAOK]] in 2018\n| fullname = Alexandros Paschalakis\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1989|7|28|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Athens]], Greece\n| height = {{height|meters=1.98}}\n| position =  [[Goalkeeper (association football)|Goalkeeper]]\n| currentclub = [[PAOK FC|PAOK]] \n| clubnumber = 31\n| youthyears1 = 2003\u20132004\n| youthclubs1 = [[AEK Athens F.C.|AEK Athens]]\n| youthyears2 = 2004\u20132005\n| youthclubs2 = [[Olympiacos F.C.|Olympiacos]]\n| youthyears3 = 2005\u20132006\n| youthclubs3 = [[GS Ilioupolis|Ilioupoli]] \n| years1 = 2006\u20132008\n| clubs1 = [[GS Ilioupolis|Ilioupoli]]           \n| caps1 = 0 \n| goals1 = 0\n| years2 = 2008\u20132012 \n| clubs2 = [[Levadiakos F.C.|Levadiakos]]       \n| caps2 = 2\n| goals2 = 0\n| years3 = 2012\u20132013 \n| clubs3 = [[PAEEK]]                  \n| caps3 = 23\n| goals3 = 0\n| years4 = 2013\u20132016 \n| clubs4=[[Panthrakikos F.C.|Panthrakikos]]     \n| caps4= 18 \n| goals4= 0\n| years5 = 2016\u20132017   \n| clubs5=[[PAS Giannina F.C.|PAS Giannina]]     \n| caps5= 27\n| goals5= 0\n| years6 = 2017\u2013\n| clubs6 = [[PAOK FC|PAOK]]\n| caps6 = 53\n| goals6 = 0\n| nationalyears1 = 2019\u2013\n|  nationalteam1 = [[Greece national football team|Greece]]\n|  nationalcaps1 = 3\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n|medaltemplates =\n| pcupdate = 1 March 2020\n| ntupdate = 15 October 2019\n}}\n\n'''Alexandros Paschalakis''' ({{lang-el|\u0391\u03bb\u03ad\u03be\u03b1\u03bd\u03b4\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2 \u03a0\u03b1\u03c3\u03c7\u03b1\u03bb\u03ac\u03ba\u03b7\u03c2}}; born 28 July 1989) is a Greek professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]] for [[PAOK FC|PAOK]] and the [[Greece national football team|Greece national team]].\n\n==Club career==\n===Early career===\nHe started playing football in Terpsithea. He was at the youth team of [[AEK Athens F.C.|AEK]] for a year and then at the youth team of [[Olympiacos F.C.|Olympiakos]] for 2 years (2003\u20132005). He moved to the team of [[GS Ilioupolis|Ilioupoli]]. At the age of 17 he transferred to the youth team of [[Galatasaray S.K. (football)|Galatasaray]] but he couldn't sign a contract due to restrictions on the number of foreign players.\n\nHe signed for [[Levadiakos F.C.|Levadiakos]] in the summer of 2008. He signed for [[PAEEK]] in the summer of 2012. [[Akhisar Belediyespor|Akhisar]] was interested in Paschalakis but he didn't want to move there.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sport24.gr/football/omades/PasGiannina/air-pasxalakhs.4564593.html|title=Air \u03a0\u03b1\u03c3\u03c7\u03b1\u03bb\u03ac\u03ba\u03b7\u03c2|date=8 March 2017|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.gazzetta.gr/match-review/article/1031257/taxidi-toy-kanithares-tis-ipeiroy-mehri-tin-kataxiosi|title=\u03a4\u03bf \u03c4\u03b1\u03be\u03af\u03b4\u03b9 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5... \u039a\u03b1\u03bd\u03b9\u03b8\u03ac\u03c1\u03b5\u03c2 \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u0397\u03c0\u03b5\u03af\u03c1\u03bf\u03c5, \u03bc\u03ad\u03c7\u03c1\u03b9 \u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u03ba\u03b1\u03c4\u03b1\u03be\u03af\u03c9\u03c3\u03b7!|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> After returning to Greece and spending six months in limbo, he signed for Panthrakikos on January 2014, but played just 13 matches until January 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.novasports.gr/podosfairo/ellada/super-league/article/67283/anakoinose-ton-pashalaki-o-panthrakikos/|title=\u0391\u03bd\u03b1\u03ba\u03bf\u03af\u03bd\u03c9\u03c3\u03b5 \u03c4\u03bf\u03bd \u03a0\u03b1\u03c3\u03c7\u03b1\u03bb\u03ac\u03ba\u03b7 \u03bf \u03a0\u03b1\u03bd\u03b8\u03c1\u03b1\u03ba\u03b9\u03ba\u03cc\u03c2|date=8 January 2014|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nHe signed for [[PAS Giannina F.C.|PAS Giannina]] on 26 January 2016, to replace [[Markos Vellidis]]' transfer to [[PAOK]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pasgiannina.gr/articles/anakoinose_pae_pas_giannina_1966_62|title=\u0391\u03bd\u03b1\u03ba\u03bf\u03af\u03bd\u03c9\u03c3\u03b7 \u03a0\u0391\u0395 \u03a0\u0391\u03a3 \u0393\u0399\u0391\u039d\u039d\u0399\u039d\u0391 1966|date=26 January 2016|website=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170729223350/http://www.pasgiannina.gr/articles/anakoinose_pae_pas_giannina_1966_62|archive-date=29 July 2017|access-date=|url-status=dead}}</ref> He didn't play at all in his first six months in Giannina. On 25 July 2017, the 28-year-old goalkeeper that was bound by a contract to the club until the summer of 2018, had made an appeal due to a delay in his annual salary. The Athenian goalie had an outstanding season playing in 27 games, out of which four in [[UEFA Europa League]]. [[PAOK]], along with [[Asteras Tripoli]] and [[Panathinaikos]] expressed interest in his acquisition, having 9 clean sheets.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sport24.gr/football/omades/PasGiannina/prosfygh-kata-toy-pas-giannina-o-pasxalakhs.4780323.html |title=\u03a0\u03c1\u03bf\u03c3\u03c6\u03c5\u03b3\u03ae \u03ba\u03b1\u03c4\u03ac \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u03a0\u0391\u03a3 \u0393\u03b9\u03ac\u03bd\u03bd\u03b9\u03bd\u03b1 \u03bf \u03a0\u03b1\u03c3\u03c7\u03b1\u03bb\u03ac\u03ba\u03b7\u03c2 |date=25 July 2017|publisher=sport24.gr |access-date=29 July 2017}}</ref> On 1 August, Paschalakis was released from [[PAS Giannina F.C.|PAS Giannina]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sport24.gr/football/omades/PasGiannina/symvivastikh-lush-pas-me-pasxalakh-poy-menei-eleutheros.4788506.html |title=\u03a3\u03c5\u03bc\u03b2\u03b9\u03b2\u03b1\u03c3\u03c4\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae \u03bb\u03cd\u03c3\u03b7 \u03a0\u0391\u03a3 \u03bc\u03b5 \u03a0\u03b1\u03c3\u03c7\u03b1\u03bb\u03ac\u03ba\u03b7 \u03c0\u03bf\u03c5 \u03bc\u03ad\u03bd\u03b5\u03b9 \u03b5\u03bb\u03b5\u03cd\u03b8\u03b5\u03c1\u03bf\u03c2 |date=1 August 2017|publisher=sport24.gr }}</ref>\n\n===PAOK===\nOn 7 August 2017, he signed a year contract with [[PAOK FC|PAOK]] for an undisclosed fee.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.paokfc.gr/nea/20170807-ston-paok-o-paschalakis/|title=\u03a3\u03c4\u03bf\u03bd \u03a0\u0391\u039f\u039a \u03bf \u03a0\u03b1\u03c3\u03c7\u03b1\u03bb\u03ac\u03ba\u03b7\u03c2|date=7 August 2017|website=|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> On 2 December 2017, he made his debut in a 3\u20130 away win against [[Xanthi F.C.|Xanthi]] A day later he renewed his contract with the club till the summer of 2020. The 28-year-old goalkeeper has increased his earnings and the release clause will be set in the region of \u20ac5 million.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sport24.gr/football/omades/Paok/ananewse-me-rhtra-5-ekat-eyrw-o-pasxalakhs.4967547.html |title=\u0391\u03bd\u03b1\u03bd\u03ad\u03c9\u03c3\u03b5 \u03bc\u03b5 \u03c1\u03ae\u03c4\u03c1\u03b1 5 \u03b5\u03ba\u03b1\u03c4. \u03b5\u03c5\u03c1\u03ce \u03bf \u03a0\u03b1\u03c3\u03c7\u03b1\u03bb\u03ac\u03ba\u03b7\u03c2! |date=3 December 2017|publisher=sport24.gr }}</ref>\n\nIt was initially planned that he would be back-up to Argentinian [[Rodrigo Rey]], but since head coach [[Razvan Lucescu]] gave him a chance, Paschalakis has made himself PAOK's starter. As of 4 February 2018, Paschalakis holds PAOK's record for most consecutive minutes without conceding, with 971 excluding stoppage time (1008 in total), before conceding in a 1\u20133 away win over PAS Giannina,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sport24.gr/football/ellada/SuperLeague/aeras-o-paok-3-1-ton-pas-sta-giannina.5061854.html|title=\u0391\u03ad\u03c1\u03b1\u03c2 \u03bf \u03a0\u0391\u039f\u039a, 3\u20131 \u03c4\u03bf\u03bd \u03a0\u0391\u03a3 \u03c3\u03c4\u03b1 \u0393\u03b9\u03ac\u03bd\u03bd\u03b9\u03bd\u03b1|access-date=8 February 2018|language=en}}</ref> to surpass current runner-up [[Kostas Chalkias]] with 859 min. Unsurprisingly, PAOK boast the [[Greek Super League|Superleague]]'s tightest defence with seven goals conceded in nineteen matches, a statistic which is largely down to Paschalakis' superb performances between the sticks.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sport24.gr/Files/o-pasxalakhs-grafei-istoria-sthn-estia-toy-paok.5051697.html|title=\u039f \u03a0\u03b1\u03c3\u03c7\u03b1\u03bb\u03ac\u03ba\u03b7\u03c2 \u03b3\u03c1\u03ac\u03c6\u03b5\u03b9 \u03b9\u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03c1\u03af\u03b1 \u03c3\u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u03b5\u03c3\u03c4\u03af\u03b1 \u03c4\u03bf\u03c5 \u03a0\u0391\u039f\u039a|access-date=30 January 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 August 2018, Paschalakis saves second-half [[Quincy Promes]] penalty in a 3\u20132 home win game for [[UEFA Champions League|UEFA Champions League Third qualifying round, 1st leg]] against [[FC Spartak Moscow|Spartak Moskva]], helping his club to maintain the win.<ref>{{cite news|title=\u039c\u03b5\u03b3\u03ac\u03bb\u03b7 \u0391\u03bd\u03b1\u03c4\u03c1\u03bf\u03c0\u03ae \u03b3\u03b9\u03b1 \u03c4\u03bf\u03bd \u03a0\u0391\u039f\u039a 3\u20132 \u03b5\u03c0\u03af \u03c4\u03b7\u03c2 \u03a3\u03c0\u03ac\u03c1\u03c4\u03b1\u03ba \u03c3\u03c4\u03b7 \u03a4\u03bf\u03cd\u03bc\u03c0\u03b1 |url=https://www.voria.gr/article/live-apo-tin-toumpa-i-megali-anametrisi-paok-vs-spartak |publisher=voria.gr|date=8 August 2018}}</ref>\nIn the first half of the [[2018\u201319 Superleague Greece|2018\u201319 season]] Paschalakis played every minute of domestic championship action, conceding a mere six goals in 15 matches while tallying an impressive nine clean sheets. On 17 January 2019, Paschalakis was awarded a new contract with PAOK through to 2022, and assuming he continues keeping the opponents off the scoreboard, PAOK will surely win the Greek championship for the first time in 34 years.<ref>{{cite news|title=\u03a0\u03b1\u03c3\u03c7\u03b1\u03bb\u03ac\u03ba\u03b7\u03c2 \u03c9\u03c2 \u03c4\u03bf 2022 \u03c3\u03c4\u03bf\u03bd \u03a0\u0391\u039f\u039a! |url=http://www.gazzetta.gr/football/superleague/article/1314678/pashalakis-os-2022-ston-paok |publisher=gazzetta.gr|date=17 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 25 April 2019, made a number of saves in a semifinal second leg [[Greek Cup]] game against [[Asteras Tripolis]], helping PAOK's title defence of the Greek Cup, as the newly crowned [[Super League]] champions secured a 0\u20130 draw in Tripoli to progress 2\u20130 on aggregate.  PAOK for the third consecutive season will meet [[AEK Athens]] in the Greek Cup final.<ref>{{cite news|title=\u0391\u03c3\u03c4\u03ad\u03c1\u03b1\u03c2 \u03a4\u03c1\u03af\u03c0\u03bf\u03bb\u03b7\u03c2 \u2013 \u03a0\u0391\u039f\u039a 0\u20130 |url=http://www.gazzetta.gr/football/kypello-elladas/article/1349470/asteras-tripolis-paok-0-0 |publisher=gazzetta.gr|date=25 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nOn 5 October 2018 Greece coach [[Michael Skibbe]] called up goalie Alexandros Paschalakis for upcoming [[2018\u201319 UEFA Nations League]] matches against [[Hungary national football team|Hungary]] and [[finland national football team|Finland]] for [[UEFA Nations League]]. ''\"All players dream of someday representing their country and I am happy for this opportunity. I waited for a long time for this call,\"'' said Paschalakis.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.sport24.gr/football/omades/Paok/pasxalakhs-perimena-polu-kairo-thn-klhsh-sthn-ethnikh-ellados.5329166.html |title=\u03a0\u03b1\u03c3\u03c7\u03b1\u03bb\u03ac\u03ba\u03b7\u03c2: \"\u03a0\u03b5\u03c1\u03af\u03bc\u03b5\u03bd\u03b1 \u03c0\u03bf\u03bb\u03cd \u03ba\u03b1\u03b9\u03c1\u03cc \u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u03ba\u03bb\u03ae\u03c3\u03b7 \u03c3\u03c4\u03b7\u03bd \u0395\u03b8\u03bd\u03b9\u03ba\u03ae \u0395\u03bb\u03bb\u03ac\u03b4\u03bf\u03c2\"|publisher= sport24.gr| language=el|date=5 October 2018}}</ref> On 30 May 2019, he made his debut in a 2\u20131 [[Exhibition match|friendly game]] away loss against [[Turkey national football team|Turkey]].\n\n==Career statistics ==\n{{updated|4 March 2020}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center;\"\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Club\n!rowspan=2|Season\n! colspan=\"3\" |[[Championship]]\n!colspan=2|[[Cup]]\n!colspan=2|[[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]]\n!colspan=2|[[UEFA Europa League|Europa League]]\n!colspan=2|Total\n|-\n!Division\n!Apps\n!Goals\n!Apps\n!Goals\n!Apps\n!Goals\n!Apps\n!Goals\n!Apps\n!Goals\n|-\n| rowspan=3 |[[Panthrakikos F.C.|Panthrakikos]]\n|[[2013\u201314 Superleague Greece|2013\u201314]]\n| rowspan=\"3\" |[[Super League Greece]]\n|5||0||0||0||0||0||0||0||5||0 \n|-\n|[[2014\u201315 Superleague Greece|2014\u201315]]\n|4||0||3||0||0||0||0||0||7||0 \n|-\n|[[2015\u201316 Superleague Greece|2015\u201316]]\n|4||0||2||0||0||0||0||0||6||0 \n|-\n| rowspan=1 |[[PAS Giannina F.C.|PAS Giannina]]\n|[[2016\u201317 Superleague Greece|2016\u201317]]\n|[[Super League Greece]]\n|20||0||3||0||0||0||4||0||27||0 \n|-\n| rowspan=3 |[[PAOK F.C.|PAOK]]\n|[[2017\u201318 Superleague Greece|2017\u201318]]\n| rowspan=\"3\" |[[Super League Greece]]\n|17||0||7||0||0||0||0||0||25||0 \n|-\n|[[2018\u201319 Superleague Greece|2018\u201319]]\n|30||0||6||0||6||0||6||0||48||0 \n|-\n|[[2019\u201320 Superleague Greece|2019\u201320]]\n|6||0||4||0||2||0||2||0||14||0 \n|-\n! colspan=\"3\" | Career totals\n!86!!0!!25!!0!!8!!0!!12!!0!!131!!0\n|}\n\n==Honours==\n\n===Club===\n;PAOK\n*[[Super League Greece]]: [[2018\u201319 Superleague Greece|2018\u201319]]\n*[[Greek Football Cup|Greek Cup]]: [[2017\u201318 Greek Football Cup|2017\u201318]],<ref>https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2018/02/28/greece/cup/panionios-nfc/paok-fc/2744640/</ref> [[2018\u201319 Greek Football Cup|2018\u201319]]\n\n===Individual===\n*[[Greek football PSAP awards#Superleague Greece Awards|Super League Greece Greek Best Goalkeeper of the Year]]: [[2018\u201319 Superleague Greece|2018\u201319]]\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*{{soccerway|alexandros-paschalakis/67710}}\n*{{UEFA player}}\n*{{NFT player|74367}}\n\n{{PAOK F.C. squad}}\n{{Navboxes\n| title = Awards\n| bg = gold\n| fg = navy\n| list1 = \n{{2018\u201319 Super League Greece Team of the Year}}\n{{Super League Greece Goalkeeper of the Year}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Paschalakis, Alexandros}}\n[[Category:1989 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Greek footballers]]\n[[Category:Greece international footballers]]\n[[Category:Super League Greece players]]\n[[Category:Levadiakos F.C. players]]\n[[Category:PAEEK players]]\n[[Category:Panthrakikos F.C. players]]\n[[Category:PAS Giannina F.C. players]]\n[[Category:PAOK FC players]]\n[[Category:Association football goalkeepers]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Athens]]\n[[Category:Cypriot Second Division players]]\n[[Category:Expatriate footballers in Cyprus]]\n[[Category:Greek expatriate footballers]]\n", "name_user": "2a02:587:3d14:8100:881:6e8d:20b2:85c6", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(added content)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alexandros_Paschalakis"}
{"title_page": "Gallo pinto", "text_new": "{{Infobox food\n| name             = Gallo Pinto\n| image            = File:CRI 07 2018 0120.jpg\n| caption          = Gallo pinto, served at breakfast with fried eggs, [[Cooking banana|plantain]], bacon, avocado, a corn tortilla and [[sour cream]]\n| country          = Nicaragua<ref>https://theculturetrip.com/central-america/costa-rica/articles/costa-rica-vs-nicaragua-who-really-invented-gallo-pinto/</ref>{{Unreliable source|sure=y|reason=Source is a blog. Doesn't directly support the information [[WP:RS]].|date=November 2019}}\nCosta Rica<ref name=\"vega\">{{cite journal |last1=Vega Jim\u00e9nez |first1=Patricia |title=El Gallo Pinto |journal=Food, Culture & Society |date=2012 |volume=15 |issue=2 |pages=223\u2013240 |doi=10.2752/175174412X13233545145228 }}</ref><ref name=\"preston-werner\">{{cite journal |last1=Preston-Werner |first1=Theresa |title=\"Gallo Pinto\": Tradition, Memory, and Identity in Costa Rican Foodways |journal=Journal of American Folklore |date=1 January 2009 |volume=122 |issue=483 |pages=11\u201327 |jstor=20487644 |doi=10.1353/jaf.0.0043 }}</ref><br>\n| region           = Central America\n| course           = Breakfast and Dinner\n| served           = Hot\n| main_ingredient  = Rice, Beans\n| variations       = Regional variations\n| other            = \n}}\n\n'''''Gallo pinto''''' or '''''gallopinto'''''<ref>[[Royal Spanish Academy]] y [[Association of Academies of the Spanish Language]] (2014). [http://dle.rae.es/Gallo+pinto \u00abgallopinto\u00bb]. ''Diccionario de la lengua espa\u00f1ola'' (23.\u00aa edici\u00f3n). Madrid: Spain. {{ISBN|978-84-670-4189-7}}. Consulted October 19, 2018.</ref> is a traditional dish from [[Central America]], made particularly in [[Nicaragua]] and [[Costa Rica]].<ref name=\"vega\" /><ref name=\"preston-werner\" />  Consisting of [[rice and beans]] as a base, gallo pinto has a long history and is important to various Latin American cultures. The beans in gallo pinto are quickly cooked until the juice is almost consumed, then combined with prepared rice and other ingredients such as cooked bell peppers, chopped onions, and garlic.\n\n==Etymology==\nGallo pinto means \"spotted rooster\" in [[Spanish language|Spanish]]. The name is said to originate in the multi-colored or speckled appearance that results from cooking the rice with black or red beans. The term may also be shortened depending on the region.\n\n== History ==\nGallo pinto is one of many various [[Latin America]]n plates which involve the preparation of the most integral ingredients for many cultures: rice and beans. Gallo pinto is considered to be a product of [[mestizo]]s; a combination of beans, cultivated by [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Indigenous people]] of [[Pre-Columbian era|pre-Columbian]] time, and rice, a grain introduced by the [[Spain|Spanish.]] The cooking and preparation is heavily influenced by [[African cuisine|African cooking]].<ref name=ambassade_costarica>{{cite web |title=Ambassade Costa Rica -- Gastronom\u00eda costarricense |url=http://www.ambassade-costarica.org/le_costa_rica/costa_rica_es/Cultura/Gastronomia%20costarricense.html |accessdate=29 February 2012 |language=Spanish |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120330172234/http://www.ambassade-costarica.org/le_costa_rica/costa_rica_es/Cultura/Gastronomia%20costarricense.html |archivedate=30 March 2012 }}</ref><ref>Ross, 2001, p. 64</ref>\n\nRice, originally from Asia, was introduced by Arabs in Spain and became a main but versatile ingredients in the fifteenth and sixteenth century. With the Spanish conquest of the Americas, the Spanish introduced rice quickly to Mexico and South America. It is suggested that within the eighteenth century, the cultivation of rice became relevant to Central America. Asian rice was cultivated by Africans in the neolithic period, and with their arrival to the Americas as slaves by Europeans, they were already accustomed to eating rice. So this occurred as well with beans, which were cultivated centuries prior in the Americas. On their travels to America, slaves were given bowls and a wooden spoon from which they ate twice a day. They ate primarily beans and European or African rice, along with maize, yams, cassava and sponge cake.<ref>Ross, 2001, p. 62</ref><ref name=\":0\">Ross, 2001, p. 63</ref>\n\nAs Africans were forced to settle in the continent, various forms of rice and beans began to take form. Because the Americas had many types of beans cultivated by Indigenous people, they gave rise to a range of dishes when combined with rice.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Variations==\nIn the Americas, there are many dishes with a base of beans and rice, which vary in their cooking and additional ingredients. Variations exist regionally, as cultures shape the dishes to their own preferences. In countries near or in the Caribbean, these dishes are simply known as ''rice and beans'', in which the dish is cooked in coconut milk. Variations of gallo pinto are the following:\n\n* [[Brazil|Brasil]]: ''feijoada''\n* [[Chile]]: ''arroz con porotos.''\n* [[Colombia]]: ''[[calentao]]''\n** [[Archipelago of San Andr\u00e9s, Providencia and Santa Catalina]]:  ''rice and beans'' \n* [[Costa Rica]]:  ''gallo pinto''; there are three main variations: \n** [[Costa Rican Central Valley|Valle Central]]: gallo pinto is more moist, less greasy and is seasoned with chili, cilantro and onions. One variant includes Lizano sauce, an English sauce that was created and patented for the first time in Costa Rica by [[Salsa Lizano|Prospero Lizano]] in 1920 with native ingredients and is a version of the Worcestershire sauce.\n** [[Guanacaste Province|Guanacaste]]: with a more fatty and roasted gallo pinto; made with red beans\n** Caribbean Coast ([[Lim\u00f3n|Puerto Lim\u00f3n]] and [[Puerto Viejo de Talamanca|Puerto Viejo]]): ''rice and beans'' in which rice and beans are cooked with coconut milk and [[Habanero|habanero chili]] (locally known as Panamanian chile) is added.\n* [[Cuba]]: There are two main variations:\n** [[Moros y cristianos]]: also known as ''moros'', it is made with black beans. If made with red beans, it would be considered ''congris''.\n** Congris: made with red beans, its preparation is different from that of gallo pinto, since the beans are cooked first with onion, green chili, garlic, tomato, bay leaf, touch of cumin and oregano, salt, and dry wine; before they soften completely, the raw rice is added, letting them cook together, until they consume the broth and the rice is dry and loose. The beans are also prepared in their broth with the rice separate.\n* [[Dominican Republic]]:  ''moro;''  made with pigeon beans, similar to Panama and Puerto Rico dishes\n* [[El Salvador]]:  ''casamiento'';  despite not having a Caribbean coast, this dish is very typical in El Salvador.;\n* [[Guatemala]]:  ''casado''; regionally known as ''gallo pinto'' and ''rice and beans''\n** On the Caribbean coast and parts of eastern or eastern Guatemala ([[Izabal Department|Izabal]]): it is known as ''rice and beans'' and it includes coconut milk.\n* [[Honduras]]:  ''casamiento''\n** Caribbean coast: ''rice and beans''\n* [[Jamaica]]:  ''rice and peas''.\n* [[Mexico]]:  ''pispiote, rice and beans''\n* [[Nicaragua]]:  ''gallo pinto''; made mainly with red beans. In addition, vegetable oil is used for cooking (includes onions). It should be added that in the Nicaraguan Caribbean Coast, as in other countries, it is called \"rice and beans\" (rice and beans) and is made with coconut milk. The Gallo Pinto can be eaten in Nicaragua at any time and is the main companion of the different dishes sold in a ''[[fritanga]]'' (food stall).\n* [[Panama]]:  ''gallopinto''\n** Caribbean coast ([[Col\u00f3n, Panama|Col\u00f3n]], [[Bocas del Toro Province|Bocas del Toro]]): known as ''rice and beans,'' and prepared with coconut milk, like in the Dominican Republic.\n* [[Peru]]: There are two main variations:\n** ''calentado'' \n** ''[[:es:Tacu-tacu|tacu-tacu]]''\n* [[Puerto Rico]]:  ''[[arroz junto]]'' and ''[[arroz con gandules]]''; made with red beans or pigeon beans, and prepared with meat all in same pot.\n* [[Trinidad & Tobago]]:  ''rice and peas''.\n* [[Venezuela]]: These dishes may include fried plantains called \"tajadas\" as it is commonly found in many Venezuelan dishes:\n** ''[[Pabell\u00f3n Criollo]]'': Made with rice, beans or refried black beans and well seasoned shredded beef. It is then surrounded by slices of ripe fried plantain. The plantain give the name \"Pabellon con barandas\".\n** ''[[Arroz con Caraotas]]'': When Pabell\u00f3n Criollo omits the fried plantains, it has a different name. It is colloquially known as \"poor man's lunch\" since it is more common in low-income families. However, it can be made and enjoyed by whomever. Fried eggs can also be included. \n** ''[[Palo A Pique Llanero]]'': Made with rice, brown beans and well seasoned shredded beef, chicken and pork. It is surrounded by slices of ripe plantain and pieces of potatoes. Some areas like [[Barinas (state)|Barinas]], [[Apure]] or [[Bol\u00edvar (state)|Bolivar]] add green plantains.\n\n==See also==\n{{Cookbook|Gallo pinto}}\n*[[Hoppin' John]] - the equivalent dish in the [[Southern United States]]\n*[[Pabell\u00f3n criollo]] - a dish with these ingredients in [[Venezuela]]\n*[[Platillo Moros y Cristianos]] - the [[Cuba]]n equivalent\n* [[List of legume dishes]]\n* {{portal-inline|Food}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Rice dishes}}\n{{Legume dishes}}\n\n[[Category:Legume dishes]]\n[[Category:Rice dishes]]\n[[Category:Costa Rican cuisine]]\n[[Category:Nicaraguan cuisine]]\n[[Category:Panamanian cuisine]]\n[[Category:Salvadoran cuisine]]\n[[Category:National dishes]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox food\n| name             = Gallo Pinto\n| image            = File:CRI 07 2018 0120.jpg\n| caption          = Gallo pinto, served at breakfast with fried eggs, [[Cooking banana|plantain]], bacon, avocado, a corn tortilla and [[sour cream]]\n| country          = Nicaragua<ref>https://theculturetrip.com/central-america/costa-rica/articles/costa-rica-vs-nicaragua-who-really-invented-gallo-pinto/</ref>{{Unreliable source|sure=y|reason=Source is a blog. Doesn't directly support the information [[WP:RS]].|date=November 2019}}\nCosta Rica<ref name=\"vega\">{{cite journal |last1=Vega Jim\u00e9nez |first1=Patricia |title=El Gallo Pinto |journal=Food, Culture & Society |date=2012 |volume=15 |issue=2 |pages=223\u2013240 |doi=10.2752/175174412X13233545145228 }}</ref><ref name=\"preston-werner\">{{cite journal |last1=Preston-Werner |first1=Theresa |title=\"Gallo Pinto\": Tradition, Memory, and Identity in Costa Rican Foodways |journal=Journal of American Folklore |date=1 January 2009 |volume=122 |issue=483 |pages=11\u201327 |jstor=20487644 |doi=10.1353/jaf.0.0043 }}</ref><br>\n| region           = Central America\n| course           = Breakfast and Dinner\n| served           = Hot\n| main_ingredient  = Rice, Beans\n| variations       = Regional variations\n| other            = \n}}\n\n'''''Gallo pinto''''' or '''''gallopinto'''''<ref>[[Royal Spanish Academy]] y [[Association of Academies of the Spanish Language]] (2014). [http://dle.rae.es/Gallo+pinto \u00abgallopinto\u00bb]. ''Diccionario de la lengua espa\u00f1ola'' (23.\u00aa edici\u00f3n). Madrid: Spain. {{ISBN|978-84-670-4189-7}}. Consulted October 19, 2018.</ref> is a traditional dish from [[Central America]], made particularly in [[Nicaragua]] and [[Costa Rica]]<ref name=\"vega\" /><ref name=\"preston-werner\" />.  Consisting of [[rice and beans]] as a base; Gallo pinto has a long history and is important to various Latin American cultures. The beans in gallo pinto are quickly cooked until the juice is almost consumed, then combined with readied rice, and other ingredients such as cooked bell peppers, chopped onions, and garlic.\n\n==Etymology==\nGallo pinto means \"spotted rooster\" in [[Spanish language|Spanish]]. The name is said to originate in the multi-colored or speckled appearance that results from cooking the rice with black or red beans. The term may also be shortened depending on the region.\n\n== History ==\nGallo pinto is one of many various [[Latin America]]n plates which involve the preparation of the most integral ingredients for many cultures: rice and beans. Gallo pinto is considered to be a product of [[mestizo]]s; a combination of beans, cultivated by [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Indigenous people]] of [[Pre-Columbian era|pre-Columbian]] time, and rice, a grain introduced by the [[Spain|Spanish.]] The cooking and preparation is heavily influenced by [[African cuisine|African cooking]].<ref name=ambassade_costarica>{{cite web |title=Ambassade Costa Rica -- Gastronom\u00eda costarricense |url=http://www.ambassade-costarica.org/le_costa_rica/costa_rica_es/Cultura/Gastronomia%20costarricense.html |accessdate=29 February 2012 |language=Spanish |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120330172234/http://www.ambassade-costarica.org/le_costa_rica/costa_rica_es/Cultura/Gastronomia%20costarricense.html |archivedate=30 March 2012 }}</ref><ref>Ross, 2001, p. 64</ref>\n\nRice, originally from Asia, was introduced by Arabs in Spain and became a main but versatile ingredients in the fifteenth and sixteenth century. With the Spanish conquest of the Americas, the Spanish introduced rice quickly to Mexico and South America. It is suggested that within the eighteenth century, the cultivation of rice became relevant to Central America. Asian rice was cultivated by Africans in the neolithic period, and with their arrival to the Americas as slaves by Europeans, they were already accustomed to eating rice. So this occurred as well with beans, which were cultivated centuries prior in the Americas. On their travels to America, slaves were given bowls and a wooden spoon from which they ate twice a day. They ate primarily beans and European or African rice, along with maize, yams, cassava and sponge cake.<ref>Ross, 2001, p. 62</ref><ref name=\":0\">Ross, 2001, p. 63</ref>\n\nAs Africans were forced to settle in the continent, various forms of rice and beans began to take form. Because the Americas had many types of beans cultivated by Indigenous people, they gave rise to a range of dishes when combined with rice.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Variations==\nIn the Americas, there are many dishes with a base of beans and rice, which vary in their cooking and additional ingredients. Variations exist regionally, as cultures shape the dishes to their own preferences. In countries near or in the Caribbean, these dishes are simply known as ''rice and beans'', in which the dish is cooked in coconut milk. Variations of gallo pinto are the following:\n\n* [[Brazil|Brasil]]: ''feijoada''\n* [[Chile]]: ''arroz con porotos.''\n* [[Colombia]]: ''[[calentao]]''\n** [[Archipelago of San Andr\u00e9s, Providencia and Santa Catalina]]:  ''rice and beans'' \n* [[Costa Rica]]:  ''gallo pinto''; there are three main variations: \n** [[Costa Rican Central Valley|Valle Central]]: gallo pinto is more moist, less greasy and is seasoned with chili, cilantro and onions. One variant includes Lizano sauce, an English sauce that was created and patented for the first time in Costa Rica by [[Salsa Lizano|Prospero Lizano]] in 1920 with native ingredients and is a version of the Worcestershire sauce.\n** [[Guanacaste Province|Guanacaste]]: with a more fatty and roasted gallo pinto; made with red beans\n** Caribbean Coast ([[Lim\u00f3n|Puerto Lim\u00f3n]] and [[Puerto Viejo de Talamanca|Puerto Viejo]]): ''rice and beans'' in which rice and beans are cooked with coconut milk and [[Habanero|habanero chili]] (locally known as Panamanian chile) is added.\n* [[Cuba]]: There are two main variations:\n** [[Moros y cristianos]]: also known as ''moros'', it is made with black beans. If made with red beans, it would be considered ''congris''.\n** Congris: made with red beans, its preparation is different from that of gallo pinto, since the beans are cooked first with onion, green chili, garlic, tomato, bay leaf, touch of cumin and oregano, salt, and dry wine; before they soften completely, the raw rice is added, letting them cook together, until they consume the broth and the rice is dry and loose. The beans are also prepared in their broth with the rice separate.\n* [[Dominican Republic]]:  ''moro;''  made with pigeon beans, similar to Panama and Puerto Rico dishes\n* [[El Salvador]]:  ''casamiento'';  despite not having a Caribbean coast, this dish is very typical in El Salvador.;\n* [[Guatemala]]:  ''casado''; regionally known as ''gallo pinto'' and ''rice and beans''\n** On the Caribbean coast and parts of eastern or eastern Guatemala ([[Izabal Department|Izabal]]): it is known as ''rice and beans'' and it includes coconut milk.\n* [[Honduras]]:  ''casamiento''\n** Caribbean coast: ''rice and beans''\n* [[Jamaica]]:  ''rice and peas''.\n* [[Mexico]]:  ''pispiote, rice and beans''\n* [[Nicaragua]]:  ''gallo pinto''; made mainly with red beans. In addition, vegetable oil is used for cooking (includes onions). It should be added that in the Nicaraguan Caribbean Coast, as in other countries, it is called \"rice and beans\" (rice and beans) and is made with coconut milk. The Gallo Pinto can be eaten in Nicaragua at any time and is the main companion of the different dishes sold in a ''[[fritanga]]'' (food stall).\n* [[Panama]]:  ''gallopinto''\n** Caribbean coast ([[Col\u00f3n, Panama|Col\u00f3n]], [[Bocas del Toro Province|Bocas del Toro]]): known as ''rice and beans,'' and prepared with coconut milk, like in the Dominican Republic.\n* [[Peru]]: There are two main variations:\n** ''calentado'' \n** ''[[:es:Tacu-tacu|tacu-tacu]]''\n* [[Puerto Rico]]:  ''[[arroz junto]]'' and ''[[arroz con gandules]]''; made with red beans or pigeon beans, and prepared with meat all in same pot.\n* [[Trinidad & Tobago]]:  ''rice and peas''.\n* [[Venezuela]]: These dishes may include fried plantains called \"tajadas\" as it is commonly found in many Venezuelan dishes:\n** ''[[Pabell\u00f3n Criollo]]'': Made with rice, beans or refried black beans and well seasoned shredded beef. It is then surrounded by slices of ripe fried plantain. The plantain give the name \"Pabellon con barandas\".\n** ''[[Arroz con Caraotas]]'': When Pabell\u00f3n Criollo omits the fried plantains, it has a different name. It is colloquially known as \"poor man's lunch\" since it is more common in low-income families. However, it can be made and enjoyed by whomever. Fried eggs can also be included. \n** ''[[Palo A Pique Llanero]]'': Made with rice, brown beans and well seasoned shredded beef, chicken and pork. It is surrounded by slices of ripe plantain and pieces of potatoes. Some areas like [[Barinas (state)|Barinas]], [[Apure]] or [[Bol\u00edvar (state)|Bolivar]] add green plantains.\n\n==See also==\n{{Cookbook|Gallo pinto}}\n*[[Hoppin' John]] - the equivalent dish in the [[Southern United States]]\n*[[Pabell\u00f3n criollo]] - a dish with these ingredients in [[Venezuela]]\n*[[Platillo Moros y Cristianos]] - the [[Cuba]]n equivalent\n* [[List of legume dishes]]\n* {{portal-inline|Food}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Rice dishes}}\n{{Legume dishes}}\n\n[[Category:Legume dishes]]\n[[Category:Rice dishes]]\n[[Category:Costa Rican cuisine]]\n[[Category:Nicaraguan cuisine]]\n[[Category:Panamanian cuisine]]\n[[Category:Salvadoran cuisine]]\n[[Category:National dishes]]\n", "name_user": "Roy McCoy", "label": "safe", "comment": "; > , etc.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gallo_pinto"}
